// MedMasters: Gynae & Obs Paper 2: Pathology in Obs & Gynae
// 250 MCQs | FIGO Staging, Miscarriage, Ectopic, Molar, IUGR, PPH, Twins, Preterm, GDM, Hypertension, APS, SLE
(function(){
  if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
  window.MM['gynae_p2_patho'] = [
    // Q1
  {q:'A 45-year-old woman presents with postcoital bleeding. Cervical biopsy reveals cervical carcinoma with stromal invasion of 3 mm depth and 7 mm width. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA1','Stage IA2','Stage IB1','Stage IB2'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IA1 is defined as measured stromal invasion of 3 mm or less in depth, microinvasive disease diagnosed only by microscopy.<br><br>This is microinvasive disease diagnosed only on microscopy, not visible clinically, with stromal invasion up to 3 mm depth and 7 mm or less in horizontal spread.<br><br>Stage IA2 (B) has invasion of 3–5 mm; Stage IB1 (C) is a visible lesion less than 2 cm; Stage IB2 (D) is a visible lesion 2–4 cm.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q2
  {q:'A patient with cervical carcinoma has stromal invasion of 6 mm depth but the lesion is not clinically visible. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA1','Stage IA2','Stage IB1','Stage IIA'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IA2 is defined as measured stromal invasion more than 3 mm and up to 5 mm in depth, microscopically identified without clinical visibility.<br><br>Stage IA disease is diagnosed on microscopy only and the distinction between IA1 and IA2 guides whether cone biopsy alone or a more radical procedure is appropriate.<br><br>Stage IA1 (A) has invasion up to 3 mm; Stage IB1 (C) applies to clinically visible lesions or those exceeding 5 mm depth; Stage IIA (D) involves upper vaginal extension.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q3 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A 38-year-old woman has a visible cervical tumor measuring 3 cm confined to the cervix. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA2','Stage IB2','Stage IIA','Stage IB1'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage IB1 is a clinically visible cervical carcinoma confined to the cervix measuring less than 4 cm in greatest dimension, with no vaginal or parametrial extension.<br><br>Stage IB disease has a significantly better prognosis than Stage II or above and is primarily treated with either radical hysterectomy or chemoradiotherapy depending on tumour bulk and patient factors.<br><br>Stage IA2 (A) is microscopic only; Stage IB2 (B) is 4–5 cm; Stage IIA (C) involves upper vaginal extension.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q4 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'A cervical carcinoma measuring 5 cm is confined to the cervix without vaginal or parametrial extension. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IB3','Stage IB2','Stage IIA1','Stage IIB'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IB3 is a clinically visible cervical carcinoma confined to the cervix measuring 5 cm or more in greatest dimension, requiring chemoradiotherapy due to its bulk.<br><br>This stage was introduced in the 2018 FIGO revision to distinguish very bulky cervical disease confined to the cervix, which carries a worse prognosis than IB1 or IB2. stage IB3 tumours are generally treated with concurrent chemoradiotherapy rather than primary surgery due to their bulk.<br><br>Stage IB2 (B) is 4–5 cm; Stage IIA1 (C) involves upper vaginal extension with tumour less than 4 cm; Stage IIB (D) involves parametrial extension.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q5 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A patient with cervical carcinoma has extension to the upper two-thirds of the vagina without parametrial invasion. Tumour measures 3 cm. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IB3','Stage IIA2','Stage IIB','Stage IIA1'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIA1 is cervical carcinoma with extension to the upper two-thirds of the vagina without parametrial invasion and with tumour less than 4 cm, with tumour less than 4 cm in size.<br><br>Vaginal extension without parametrial involvement places the tumour in Stage IIA, and the size below 4 cm specifies Stage IIA1. stage IIA represents direct spread beyond the cervix into the upper vagina and is associated with a worse prognosis than Stage IB disease.<br><br>Stage IB3 (A) is confined to the cervix; Stage IIA2 (B) applies when upper vaginal involvement accompanies a tumour 4 cm or more; Stage IIB (C) involves parametrial extension.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q6 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'A cervical tumor measuring 5 cm extends to the upper vagina but there is no parametrial invasion. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IIA1','Stage IIB','Stage IIA2','Stage IIIA'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIA2 is cervical carcinoma with upper vaginal extension, no parametrial invasion, and tumour measuring 4 cm or more, distinguishing it from IIA1 by tumour size alone.<br><br>The combination of upper vaginal spread and a tumour of 5 cm size fits Stage IIA2 precisely, distinguishing it from IIA1 based on tumour size alone. stage IIA2 tumours are typically managed with concurrent chemoradiotherapy rather than primary surgery given their bulk.<br><br>Stage IIA1 (A) applies when tumour is less than 4 cm; Stage IIB (B) involves parametrial extension; Stage IIIA (D) involves lower third vaginal extension.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q7 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'A woman with cervical cancer has tumor extension to the lower third of the vagina without parametrial or pelvic wall involvement. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IIIA','Stage IIB','Stage IIIB','Stage IVA'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIA is cervical carcinoma with extension to the lower third of the vagina without extension to the pelvic wall, a finding that upgrades the tumour regardless of size.<br><br>This is an important staging distinction as Stage IIIA disease is managed with chemoradiotherapy and carries a significantly worse prognosis than Stage IIA or IIB disease.<br><br>Stage IIB (B) involves parametrial extension only; Stage IIIB (C) involves pelvic wall extension or hydronephrosis; Stage IVA (D) involves bladder or rectal mucosal invasion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q8 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'Cervical carcinoma causes hydronephrosis due to ureteric obstruction. What FIGO stage does this represent?',
  o:['Stage IIIA','Stage IVA','Stage IIIB','Stage IVB'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIB is cervical carcinoma with extension to the pelvic wall, hydronephrosis or non-functioning kidney due to ureteric obstruction, sufficient alone to classify the tumour as Stage IIIB.<br><br>Ureteric involvement causing hydronephrosis, even in the absence of other pelvic wall disease, is sufficient to classify the tumour as Stage IIIB. this reflects the significant morbidity of ureteric obstruction and the consequent renal impairment that substantially worsens prognosis and complicates treatment planning.<br><br>Stage IIIA (A) involves only lower vaginal extension; Stage IVA (B) involves bladder or rectal mucosal invasion; Stage IVB (D) involves distant metastases.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q9
  {q:'A patient with cervical carcinoma has metastasis to pelvic lymph nodes but no distant metastasis. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IIIA','Stage IIIB','Stage IVA','Stage IIIC1'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIC1 was introduced in the 2018 revision to classify cervical carcinoma with pelvic lymph node metastasis regardless of tumour size or local extent.<br><br>Lymph node involvement, even when the primary tumour appears localised, automatically upgrades the tumour to Stage IIIC, reflecting the significantly worse prognosis associated with nodal disease. stage IIIC1 specifies pelvic lymph node involvement, while Stage IIIC2 specifies para-aortic involvement.<br><br>Stage IIIA (A) and IIIB (B) are based on local extension; Stage IVA (C) involves bladder or rectal mucosal invasion without lymph node staging.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q10
  {q:'Cervical carcinoma with para-aortic lymph node metastasis corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IIIB','Stage IIIC2','Stage IVA','Stage IVB'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIC2 classifies cervical carcinoma with para-aortic lymph node metastasis, regardless of local tumour extent or primary tumour size.<br><br>Stage IIIC2 distinguishes para-aortic from pelvic nodal involvement (Stage IIIC1) because para-aortic disease requires extended-field radiotherapy and carries a worse prognosis. The distinction between IIIC1 and IIIC2 has direct implications for radiotherapy field design and treatment intent.<br><br>Stage IIIB (A) is based on pelvic wall or ureteric involvement; Stage IVA (C) is bladder or rectal mucosal invasion; Stage IVB (D) is distant metastasis beyond pelvic nodes.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q11
  {q:'A patient with cervical carcinoma has invasion into the mucosa of the rectum. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IIIC2','Stage IIIB','Stage IVA','Stage IVB'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IVA is cervical carcinoma with spread to adjacent pelvic organs : specifically invasion of the bladder mucosa or rectal mucosa.<br><br>Mucosal invasion of the rectum (or bladder) confirms Stage IVA disease, distinguishing it from parametrial or pelvic wall extension which are Stage IIIB.<br><br>Stage IIIC2 (A) is para-aortic nodal involvement; Stage IIIB (B) is pelvic wall or ureteric obstruction; Stage IVB (D) is distant metastasis outside the pelvis.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q12
  {q:'A woman with cervical carcinoma develops lung metastases. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IVA','Stage IIIC2','Stage IIIB','Stage IVB'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage IVB is cervical carcinoma with distant metastasis beyond the pelvis : including lung, liver, bone or distant lymph nodes.<br><br>Once haematogenous or distant lymphatic spread has occurred, the disease is Stage IVB regardless of local tumour extent, and treatment is palliative rather than curative. lung metastasis from cervical carcinoma is one of the most common sites of Stage IVB disease.<br><br>Stage IVA (A) involves only adjacent pelvic organ invasion; Stage IIIC2 (B) involves para-aortic nodes; Stage IIIB (C) involves pelvic wall or ureteric obstruction : none represent distant haematogenous spread.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q13
  {q:'A 55-year-old woman presents with ovarian carcinoma involving one ovary with capsule rupture during surgery. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA','Stage IB','Stage IC1','Stage II'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IC1 is ovarian carcinoma limited to one or both ovaries with surgical spill (capsule rupture) during surgery, upgrading otherwise Stage IA disease to IC1.<br><br>The 2014 FIGO revision divided Stage IC into three subgroups to distinguish surgical spill (IC1) from pre-operative capsule rupture (IC2) from positive cytology (IC3), as each carries a different implication for prognosis and adjuvant treatment.<br><br>Stage IA (A) is one ovary with intact capsule; Stage IB (B) is both ovaries intact; Stage II (D) involves pelvic extension beyond the ovaries.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q14 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'Ovarian carcinoma with tumor on ovarian surface but confined to ovaries corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IC2','Stage IA','Stage IB','Stage II'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IC2 is ovarian carcinoma confined to one or both ovaries with pre-operative rupture of the capsule or tumour on the ovarian surface.<br><br>Tumour visible on the ovarian surface indicates capsule involvement or pre-operative rupture, distinguishing IC2 from IC1 (surgical spill) and from IC3 (positive peritoneal cytology). the 2014 FIGO revision made this distinction to better stratify prognosis and guide adjuvant treatment decisions.<br><br>Stage IA (B) requires intact capsule with no surface tumour; Stage IB (C) involves both ovaries with intact capsules; Stage II (D) involves extension beyond the ovaries.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q15 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A patient with ovarian carcinoma has malignant cells in peritoneal washings but ovaries are confined with intact capsules. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IC1','Stage IC2','Stage II','Stage IC3'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage IC3 is ovarian carcinoma confined to one or both ovaries with positive peritoneal cytology, reflecting intraperitoneal tumour cell dissemination.<br><br>Malignant cells in peritoneal washings, even with otherwise confined disease, place the tumour in Stage IC3, reflecting the biological significance of intraperitoneal tumour cell dissemination and its association with poorer outcomes.<br><br>Stage IC1 (A) is surgical spill; Stage IC2 (B) is surface tumour or pre-operative rupture; Stage II (C) involves visible pelvic extension beyond the ovaries.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q16
  {q:'Ovarian carcinoma with pelvic extension to bladder peritoneum corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IIA','Stage IIB','Stage IIIA1','Stage IC3'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIB is ovarian carcinoma with pelvic extension to other pelvic intraperitoneal tissues, including bladder peritoneum, sigmoid colon or pelvic sidewall, beyond the uterus and tubes.<br><br>Stage IIA is reserved for extension specifically to the uterus or fallopian tubes, while Stage IIB encompasses all other pelvic peritoneal extension.<br><br>Stage IIA (A) involves uterine or tubal extension specifically; Stage IIIA1 (C) involves retroperitoneal lymph nodes only; Stage IC3 (D) involves positive cytology without pelvic extension.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q17
  {q:'Ovarian carcinoma with microscopic peritoneal metastasis outside pelvis corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IIB','Stage IIIA1','Stage IIIA2','Stage IIIB'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIA2 is ovarian carcinoma with microscopic peritoneal metastasis beyond the pelvis with or without retroperitoneal lymph node involvement.<br><br>Microscopic extraperitoneal spread beyond the pelvis confirms Stage III disease, distinguishing it from Stage II which is confined to the pelvis. even microscopic Stage IIIA2 disease requires aggressive platinum-taxane chemotherapy, typically given after maximal surgical debulking.<br><br>Stage IIB (A) is pelvic extension only; Stage IIIA1 (B) is retroperitoneal lymph node metastasis only; Stage IIIB (D) is macroscopic peritoneal metastasis 2 cm or less outside the pelvis.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q18
  {q:'Ovarian carcinoma with metastasis to retroperitoneal lymph nodes only corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IIIA1','Stage IIIA2','Stage IIIB','Stage IIB'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIA1 is ovarian carcinoma with metastasis to retroperitoneal lymph nodes only : without intraperitoneal spread beyond the pelvis.<br><br>The 2014 FIGO revision recognised that isolated retroperitoneal nodal disease has a better prognosis than peritoneal Stage III disease, resulting in this dedicated substage. stage IIIA1 is further divided into IIIA1(i) with nodes up to 10 mm and IIIA1(ii) with nodes larger than 10 mm.<br><br>Stage IIIA2 (B) includes microscopic peritoneal spread; Stage IIIB (C) includes macroscopic peritoneal metastasis up to 2 cm; Stage IIB (D) is confined to the pelvis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q19
  {q:'Ovarian carcinoma with peritoneal metastasis larger than 2 cm outside pelvis corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IIIA2','Stage IIIB','Stage IIIC','Stage IVA'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIC is ovarian carcinoma with peritoneal metastasis more than 2 cm in greatest dimension outside the pelvis, with or without retroperitoneal lymph node metastasis.<br><br>Macroscopic peritoneal disease greater than 2 cm is the hallmark of Stage IIIC, which represents the most common stage at presentation and the primary target of debulking surgery. optimal debulking to no residual disease is the most important prognostic factor in Stage IIIC disease.<br><br>Stage IIIA2 (A) is microscopic extraperitoneal spread; Stage IIIB (B) is macroscopic but 2 cm or less; Stage IVA (D) is pleural effusion with malignant cytology.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q20
  {q:'Ovarian carcinoma with pleural effusion containing malignant cells corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IVA','Stage IIIC','Stage IIIB','Stage IVB'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IVA is ovarian carcinoma with pleural effusion containing malignant cells: the presence of malignant cytology in pleural fluid confirms extraperitoneal spread beyond the abdomen, upgrading the tumour to Stage IV regardless of the extent of abdominal disease.<br><br>Stage IVA is managed with platinum-based chemotherapy, often given as neoadjuvant treatment followed by interval debulking surgery in suitable patients.<br><br>Stage IIIC (B) and IIIB (C) are confined to the peritoneal cavity; Stage IVB (D) involves liver parenchymal metastasis or distant organ involvement beyond the pleural space.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q21 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'Ovarian carcinoma with liver parenchymal metastasis corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IIIC','Stage IVB','Stage IVA','Stage IIIA'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IVB is ovarian carcinoma with parenchymal metastasis to liver or spleen, or metastasis to extra-abdominal organs including the lungs or inguinal lymph nodes.<br><br>Liver parenchymal involvement, as opposed to liver surface peritoneal deposits, specifically defines Stage IVB disease, reflecting haematogenous rather than peritoneal spread. this distinction is clinically important as peritoneal liver surface deposits may be resectable, whereas parenchymal metastases generally are not.<br><br>Stage IIIC (A) is peritoneal metastasis more than 2 cm; Stage IVA (C) is pleural effusion with malignant cells; Stage IIIA (D) is microscopic or nodal spread only.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q22 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'The most common histological type of ovarian carcinoma is:',
  o:['Serous cystadenocarcinoma','Mucinous carcinoma','Endometrioid carcinoma','Clear cell carcinoma'],a:0,
  e:`Serous cystadenocarcinoma is the most common histological type of ovarian carcinoma, accounting for approximately 50–70% of all epithelial ovarian cancers.<br><br>Epithelial tumours account for over 90% of all malignant ovarian tumours; the serous subtype is the most biologically aggressive and the most common cause of ovarian cancer death.<br><br>Mucinous (B), endometrioid (C) and clear cell (D) carcinomas are less common epithelial subtypes with distinct molecular profiles and varying sensitivities to platinum-based chemotherapy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q23
  {q:'A young woman with ovarian tumor associated with elevated AFP most likely has:',
  o:['Granulosa cell tumor','Yolk sac tumor','Dysgerminoma','Serous cystadenocarcinoma'],a:1,
  e:`A yolk sac tumour (endodermal sinus tumour) is a malignant germ cell tumour that secretes alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), making AFP elevation the defining tumour marker for this diagnosis.<br><br>It occurs predominantly in young women and girls, presenting as a rapidly growing ovarian mass with dramatically elevated serum AFP levels. aFP is used for both initial diagnosis and for monitoring treatment response and detecting recurrence after chemotherapy.<br><br>Granulosa cell tumour (A) secretes inhibin and oestrogen; dysgerminoma (C) is associated with LDH and occasionally hCG; serous cystadenocarcinoma (D) is an epithelial tumour associated with CA-125.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q24 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'A granulosa cell tumor of ovary commonly secretes:',
  o:['hCG','AFP','Estrogen','Androgens'],a:2,
  e:`Granulosa cell tumours are sex cord stromal tumours that secrete oestrogen, accounting for the clinical manifestations of oestrogen excess, including abnormal uterine bleeding and postmenopausal bleeding.<br><br>Abnormal uterine bleeding, postmenopausal bleeding and precocious puberty in young girls: granulosa cell tumours are the most common subtype of sex cord stromal tumours, accounting for over 70% of this group.<br><br>hCG (A) is produced by trophoblastic tumours; AFP (B) is produced by yolk sac tumours; androgens (D) are produced by Sertoli-Leydig cell tumours causing virilisation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q25 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'The tumor marker most commonly elevated in epithelial ovarian carcinoma is:',
  o:['AFP','hCG','CEA','CA-125'],a:3,
  e:`CA-125 is the most widely used tumour marker in epithelial ovarian carcinoma, particularly serous carcinoma, and is elevated in approximately 80% of patients with advanced disease.<br><br>It is used for monitoring treatment response, detecting recurrence, and in combination with ultrasound for pre-operative assessment of pelvic masses using the Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI).<br><br>AFP (A) is elevated in yolk sac tumours; hCG (B) in trophoblastic disease; CEA (C) is a marker for colorectal cancer and mucinous ovarian tumours.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q26
  {q:'A patient with cervical intraepithelial neoplasia grade III has:',
  o:['Mild dysplasia','Moderate dysplasia','Severe dysplasia / carcinoma in situ','Microinvasive carcinoma'],a:2,
  e:`CIN III corresponds to severe dysplasia or carcinoma in situ : full-thickness epithelial abnormality without stromal invasion, the most immediate precursor to invasive cervical carcinoma.<br><br>Undifferentiated abnormal cells occupy the full thickness of the squamous epithelium, representing the highest grade of cervical intraepithelial neoplasia and the most immediate precursor to invasive cervical carcinoma.<br><br>CIN I (A) is mild dysplasia affecting the lower third of the epithelium; CIN II (B) is moderate dysplasia affecting the lower two-thirds; microinvasive carcinoma (D) has already breached the basement membrane.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q27
  {q:'The most important etiological factor in cervical carcinoma is infection with:',
  o:['HPV','HSV','Chlamydia','CMV'],a:0,
  e:`Human papillomavirus (HPV) infection, particularly persistent infection with high-risk types 16 and 18, is the most important etiological factor in cervical carcinoma, present in virtually 100% of cases.<br><br>HPV E6 and E7 oncoproteins inactivate the tumour suppressor proteins p53 and pRb respectively, driving malignant transformation of cervical epithelial cells. the introduction of HPV vaccination programmes targeting types 6, 11, 16 and 18 has dramatically reduced CIN and cervical cancer incidence in vaccinated populations.<br><br>HSV (B), Chlamydia (C) and CMV (D) are associated with other genital infections but are not the primary aetiological agents in cervical carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q28
  {q:'The HPV types most strongly associated with cervical carcinoma are:',
  o:['6 and 11','16 and 18','31 and 45','18 and 33'],a:1,
  e:`HPV types 16 and 18 are the high-risk oncogenic types most strongly associated with cervical carcinoma, together accounting for approximately 70% of all cervical cancers worldwide.<br><br>Type 16 predominates in squamous cell carcinoma while type 18 is more commonly associated with adenocarcinoma of the cervix. the quadrivalent and nonavalent HPV vaccines include types 16 and 18 as primary targets, with demonstrated high efficacy against CIN and cervical cancer.<br><br>Types 6 and 11 (A) cause genital warts but not cancer; types 31 and 45 (C) and 18 and 33 (D) are partially oncogenic but less prevalent than 16 and 18.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q29
  {q:'A Krukenberg tumor of the ovary most commonly originates from primary carcinoma of the:',
  o:['Stomach','Colon','Pancreas','Breast'],a:0,
  e:`Krukenberg tumours are ovarian metastases associated with primary cancers of the stomach, colon and breast: the stomach is the most common primary site, producing the classic Krukenberg tumour characterised by mucin-secreting signet ring cells within a cellular stroma on histology.<br><br>Krukenberg tumours account for approximately 1–2% of all ovarian tumours and typically present bilaterally as solid ovarian masses : their bilateral nature is an important clinical clue to their metastatic origin.<br><br>Colon (B) and breast (D) are secondary causes; pancreas (C) may occasionally metastasise to the ovary but is not the most common primary site for Krukenberg tumours.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q30
  {q:'A woman with hydatidiform mole later develops choriocarcinoma with lung metastases. What is the FIGO stage of gestational trophoblastic neoplasia?',
  o:['Stage I','Stage II','Stage III','Stage IV'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage III gestational trophoblastic neoplasia (GTN) is disease extending outside the uterus but limited to the lungs, the most common site of metastatic spread in GTN.<br><br>Lung metastases from GTN, the most common site of metastatic spread, define Stage III disease regardless of hCG levels or treatment history. gTN arising after molar pregnancy, including choriocarcinoma, is highly chemosensitive; even Stage III disease has cure rates exceeding 90% with appropriate combination chemotherapy.<br><br>Stage I (B) is confined to the uterus; Stage II (D) involves genital structures only; Stage IV (C) involves liver, brain or other non-pulmonary distant sites.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q31
  {q:'Gestational trophoblastic neoplasia with metastasis to the brain is classified as:',
  o:['Stage II','Stage IV','Stage III','Stage IVB'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IV gestational trophoblastic neoplasia involves metastasis to the liver, brain or other non-pulmonary distant sites, the highest risk category in gestational trophoblastic neoplasia.<br><br>Brain metastases from GTN represent the highest risk category and require intensive combination chemotherapy, often including intrathecal methotrexate, as well as whole-brain radiotherapy in some protocols.<br><br>Stage II (A) involves genital structures; Stage III (C) is pulmonary metastasis only; Stage IVB (D) is not a recognised FIGO substage for GTN.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q32
  {q:'A 52-year-old postmenopausal woman presents with abnormal vaginal bleeding. Endometrial biopsy reveals carcinoma confined to the endometrium without myometrial invasion. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA','Stage IB','Stage II','Stage IIIA'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IA endometrial carcinoma is disease confined to the endometrium or with less than half myometrial invasion, carrying an excellent prognosis exceeding 90% five-year survival.<br><br>No myometrial invasion (or invasion less than 50%) classifies the tumour as Stage IA : this carries an excellent prognosis with 5-year survival exceeding 90% following surgical treatment with total hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy.<br><br>Stage IB (B) is 50% or more myometrial invasion; Stage II (C) involves cervical stromal invasion; Stage IIIA (D) involves uterine serosa or adnexa.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q33
  {q:'A 60-year-old woman is diagnosed with endometrial carcinoma extending to the cervical stroma. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA','Stage IIA','Stage IIB','Stage IIIA'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIA endometrial carcinoma involves invasion of the cervical stroma but is confined to the uterus, not extending beyond the uterus.<br><br>Not extending beyond it: cervical stromal involvement upgrades the tumour from Stage I to Stage II, reflecting the increased risk of parametrial and lymphatic spread associated with cervical extension.<br><br>Stage IA (A) is confined to the endometrium or superficial myometrium; Stage IIB (C) is not a recognised endometrial carcinoma substage; Stage IIIA (D) involves uterine serosa or adnexa.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q34
  {q:'A patient with cervical carcinoma shows parametrial invasion but no extension to the pelvic wall. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IIA','Stage IIA2','Stage IIB','Stage IIIB'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIB cervical carcinoma is defined by parametrial invasion without extension to the pelvic sidewall, the key distinction from Stage IIA upper vaginal extension.<br><br>Parametrial involvement indicates spread beyond the cervix into the supporting ligamentous tissue of the pelvis, which is the key distinction between Stage IIA (upper vaginal extension only) and Stage IIB.<br><br>Stage IIA (A, B) involves upper vaginal extension without parametrial invasion; Stage IIIB (D) requires extension to the pelvic sidewall or hydronephrosis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q35 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A 48-year-old woman with cervical cancer has tumor extension to the pelvic wall and hydronephrosis. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IIB','Stage IIIA','Stage IVA','Stage IIIB'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIB cervical carcinoma involves extension to the pelvic wall and/or hydronephrosis or non-functioning kidney, either finding alone sufficient for Stage IIIB classification.<br><br>Pelvic wall extension or ureteric obstruction, either finding alone is sufficient, classifies the tumour as Stage IIIB and is associated with a substantially worse prognosis than Stage IIB parametrial disease. stage IIIB disease is always managed with chemoradiotherapy; 5-year survival rates are approximately 30–40%.<br><br>Stage IIB (A) is parametrial invasion without pelvic wall involvement; Stage IIIA (B) is lower vaginal extension only; Stage IVA (C) requires bladder or rectal mucosal invasion.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q36
  {q:'A patient with cervical carcinoma shows invasion into the mucosa of the bladder. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IIIB','Stage IVA','Stage IIIC2','Stage IVB'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IVA is cervical carcinoma with invasion into the mucosa of the bladder or rectum, with mucosal invasion required to confirm Stage IVA.<br><br>Mucosal, not just serosal, invasion of adjacent organs is required to classify disease as Stage IVA; bullous oedema of the bladder alone does not constitute Stage IVA without biopsy-confirmed mucosal invasion.<br><br>Stage IIIB (A) is pelvic wall extension without mucosal organ invasion; Stage IIIC2 (C) is para-aortic nodal disease; Stage IVB (D) is distant metastasis beyond the pelvis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q37
  {q:'A 65-year-old woman is diagnosed with ovarian carcinoma limited to one ovary with intact capsule and no ascites. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA','Stage IB','Stage IC1','Stage II'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IA ovarian carcinoma is defined as tumour limited to one ovary with an intact capsule, no tumour on the ovarian surface, negative peritoneal washings and no ascites.<br><br>Stage IA disease carries the best prognosis among ovarian cancers, with 5-year survival rates exceeding 90%. well-differentiated Stage IA disease may be managed conservatively with fertility-sparing surgery in young women; adjuvant chemotherapy is not routinely indicated.<br><br>Stage IB (B) involves both ovaries with intact capsules; Stage IC1 (C) involves surgical spill; Stage II (D) involves extension beyond the ovaries into the pelvis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q38
  {q:'A patient with ovarian carcinoma involving both ovaries but confined to the ovaries with intact capsules. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA','Stage IB','Stage IC2','Stage IIA'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IB ovarian carcinoma is defined as tumour limited to both ovaries with intact capsules, no tumour on the ovarian surface, negative peritoneal washings and no ascites.<br><br>Bilateral ovarian involvement without capsule rupture or peritoneal spread is the defining feature of Stage IB, carrying a prognosis similar to Stage IA. staging laparotomy with washings, omental biopsy and lymph node sampling is essential to accurately confirm Stage IB status.<br><br>Stage IA (A) is limited to one ovary; Stage IC2 (C) involves capsule rupture or surface tumour; Stage IIA (D) involves extension to the uterus or tubes.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q39
  {q:'A woman with ovarian carcinoma confined to the ovaries but with capsule rupture during surgery. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA','Stage IB','Stage IC','Stage II'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IC ovarian carcinoma includes disease confined to one or both ovaries but with capsule rupture (surgical spill = IC1, pre-operative rupture or surface tumour = IC2) or positive peritoneal cytology (IC3).<br><br>Surgical capsule rupture during oophorectomy upgrades otherwise Stage IA or IB disease to IC1 : with important implications for adjuvant chemotherapy decisions. this staging upgrade reflects the potential dissemination of tumour cells into the peritoneal cavity that capsule rupture represents.<br><br>Stage IA (A) and IB (B) both require intact capsules; Stage II (D) requires visible pelvic extension beyond the ovaries.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q40
  {q:'Ovarian carcinoma involving one or both ovaries with pelvic extension to the uterus. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IC3','Stage II','Stage IIIA1','Stage IIB'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage II ovarian carcinoma is tumour involving one or both ovaries with extension to other pelvic intraperitoneal tissues, encompassing both Stage IIA and IIB pelvic extension.<br><br>Stage IIA specifically involves extension to or implants on the uterus or fallopian tubes, while Stage IIB involves other pelvic peritoneal tissue : both remain Stage II because the disease is confined to the pelvis.<br><br>Stage IC3 (A) is confined to the ovaries with positive cytology; Stage IIIA1 (C) involves retroperitoneal lymph nodes without intraperitoneal spread; Stage IIB (D) is other pelvic extension beyond uterus and tubes.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q41
  {q:'A patient with ovarian carcinoma has peritoneal metastasis outside the pelvis with deposits 1.5 cm in size. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IIIA2','Stage IIIC','Stage IVA','Stage IIIB'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIB ovarian carcinoma is macroscopic peritoneal metastasis beyond the pelvis measuring 2 cm or less in greatest dimension, with or without retroperitoneal lymph node involvement.<br><br>Deposits of 1.5 cm outside the pelvis fit precisely into Stage IIIB, distinguishing it from IIIA2 (microscopic only) and IIIC (greater than 2 cm). optimal surgical debulking to no macroscopic residual disease remains the most important prognostic factor in Stage III disease.<br><br>Stage IIIA2 (A) is microscopic peritoneal spread only; Stage IIIC (B) is deposits greater than 2 cm; Stage IVA (C) requires pleural effusion with malignant cytology.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q42
  {q:'Ovarian carcinoma with liver parenchymal metastasis is classified as:',
  o:['Stage IIIC','Stage IVA','Stage IV','Stage IIIA1'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IVB ovarian carcinoma includes parenchymal liver or splenic metastasis, representing haematogenous spread beyond the peritoneal cavity, as distinct from peritoneal surface deposits on the liver.<br><br>Liver parenchymal involvement, as distinct from peritoneal surface deposits on the liver, places the disease in Stage IV, specifically Stage IVB. stage IV disease requires neoadjuvant chemotherapy followed by interval debulking in most cases, as upfront surgery rarely achieves optimal debulking.<br><br>Stage IIIC (A) is large peritoneal deposits but no parenchymal organ involvement; Stage IVA (B) is pleural effusion with malignant cytology; Stage IIIA1 (D) is isolated retroperitoneal nodal disease.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q43
  {q:'A 45-year-old woman is diagnosed with endometrial carcinoma extending into the upper half of the myometrium. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IB','Stage IA','Stage II','Stage IIIA'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IB endometrial carcinoma is defined as tumour invading 50% or more of the myometrial thickness while remaining confined to the uterine corpus.<br><br>The depth of myometrial invasion is the critical determinant of Stage I substaging : 50% or more invasion (Stage IB) carries a higher risk of lymphovascular space invasion, nodal metastasis and recurrence than Stage IA.<br><br>Stage IA (B) is less than 50% myometrial invasion; Stage II (C) involves cervical stromal extension; Stage IIIA (D) involves uterine serosa or adnexal spread.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q44
  {q:'Endometrial carcinoma invading the serosa of the uterus or adnexa is staged as:',
  o:['Stage IB','Stage IIIB','Stage IIIC1','Stage IIIA'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIA endometrial carcinoma involves tumour spread to the uterine serosa or adnexa (ovaries or fallopian tubes), representing penetration beyond the myometrium to adnexal structures.<br><br>Serosal involvement indicates penetration through the full thickness of the myometrium, or direct extension to adjacent adnexal structures : both represent disease that has escaped the uterine corpus and carries a substantially worse prognosis than Stage I or II disease.<br><br>Stage IB (A) is 50% or more myometrial invasion confined to the corpus; Stage IIIB (B) involves vaginal or parametrial spread; Stage IIIC1 (C) involves pelvic lymph nodes.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q45 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'Endometrial carcinoma with vaginal involvement but no distant metastasis corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IIIB','Stage IIIA','Stage IIIC1','Stage IVA'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIB endometrial carcinoma involves spread to the vagina and/or parametrium by direct extension or metastatic implant, upgrading the tumour regardless of primary uterine extent.<br><br>Vaginal involvement, whether by direct extension or implant, upgrades the tumour to Stage IIIB, reflecting spread beyond the uterus without distant metastasis. Stage IIIB disease is managed with a combination of surgery, pelvic radiotherapy and systemic chemotherapy.<br><br>Stage IIIA (B) is serosal or adnexal involvement; Stage IIIC1 (C) is pelvic lymph node metastasis; Stage IVA (D) involves bladder or rectal mucosal invasion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q46 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A patient with endometrial carcinoma has metastasis to pelvic lymph nodes only. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IIIA','Stage IIIB','Stage IIIC2','Stage IIIC1'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIC1 endometrial carcinoma involves pelvic lymph node metastasis without para-aortic involvement, significantly worsening prognosis and requiring extended-field radiotherapy with systemic chemotherapy.<br><br>Nodal disease upgrades the tumour to Stage IIIC regardless of local uterine extent, requiring extended-field radiotherapy and systemic chemotherapy. FIGO staging of endometrial carcinoma uses surgical-pathological findings; lymph node assessment is therefore an essential component of comprehensive surgical staging.<br><br>Stage IIIA (A) is serosal or adnexal spread; Stage IIIB (B) is vaginal or parametrial involvement; Stage IIIC2 (C) is para-aortic lymph node metastasis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q47 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'Metastasis of endometrial carcinoma to para-aortic lymph nodes corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IIIC1','Stage IIIC2','Stage IVA','Stage IVB'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IIIC2 endometrial carcinoma involves para-aortic lymph node metastasis with or without pelvic nodal involvement, requiring extended-field para-aortic radiotherapy.<br><br>Para-aortic nodal disease carries a worse prognosis than isolated pelvic nodal metastasis (Stage IIIC1) and requires extended-field radiotherapy targeting the para-aortic region in addition to systemic chemotherapy. the distinction between IIIC1 and IIIC2 has direct implications for radiotherapy field planning and chemotherapy selection.<br><br>Stage IIIC1 (A) is pelvic nodes only; Stage IVA (C) is bladder or rectal mucosal invasion; Stage IVB (D) is distant haematogenous metastasis.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q48
  {q:'A patient with endometrial carcinoma has invasion of bladder mucosa. According to FIGO, what stage is this?',
  o:['Stage IIIC2','Stage IIIB','Stage IVA','Stage IVB'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IVA endometrial carcinoma involves invasion of the bladder or bowel mucosa Cystoscopic biopsy is required to confirm mucosal involvement.<br><br>Cystoscopic biopsy confirmation is required; bladder compression alone without mucosal invasion does not constitute Stage IVA. Stage IVA endometrial carcinoma is managed with palliative or individualised intent, combining surgery where feasible with pelvic radiotherapy and systemic chemotherapy.<br><br>Stage IIIC2 (A) is para-aortic nodal disease; Stage IIIB (B) is vaginal or parametrial involvement; Stage IVB (D) is inguinal, peritoneal or distant haematogenous metastasis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q49
  {q:'A woman with vulvar carcinoma has tumor confined to vulva measuring less than 2 cm with no lymph node involvement. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA','Stage IB','Stage II','Stage III'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IA vulvar carcinoma is tumour confined to the vulva measuring 2 cm or less with stromal invasion of 1 mm or less and no lymph node metastasis.<br><br>Stage IA tumours can be managed with wide local excision alone without lymph node assessment, as the risk of inguinal nodal metastasis with 1 mm or less stromal invasion is less than 1%.<br><br>Stage IB (B) is confined to the vulva but with more than 1 mm stromal invasion; Stage II (C) involves adjacent perineal structures; Stage III (D) involves inguinal lymph nodes.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q50
  {q:'Vulvar carcinoma greater than 2 cm but confined to vulva without nodal involvement. What is the FIGO stage?',
  o:['Stage IA','Stage IB','Stage II','Stage IIIA'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IB vulvar carcinoma is tumour confined to the vulva measuring more than 2 cm or with stromal invasion greater than 1 mm, without regional lymph node metastasis.<br><br>Stage IB requires bilateral inguinofemoral lymph node assessment, via sentinel lymph node biopsy or full lymphadenectomy, because the risk of nodal metastasis increases substantially with deeper invasion and larger tumour size.<br><br>Stage IA (A) requires 2 cm or less and 1 mm or less stromal invasion; Stage II (C) involves adjacent perineal structures; Stage IIIA (D) involves positive inguinal nodes.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q51 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'Vulvar carcinoma with positive inguinofemoral lymph nodes is staged as:',
  o:['Stage II','Stage IVA','Stage IVB','Stage III'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage III vulvar carcinoma involves any size tumour with spread to regional lymph nodes, inguinofemoral nodes, regardless of local tumour extent.<br><br>Positive inguinal nodes automatically upgrade vulvar carcinoma to Stage III, with substaging based on the number and nature of positive nodes (Stage IIIA for 1 or 2 nodes with involvement up to 5 mm; IIIB for 3 or more nodes or nodes with extracapsular spread).<br><br>Stage II (A) involves adjacent perineal structures without nodal disease; Stage IVA (B) involves upper urethral or rectal mucosal invasion; Stage IVB (C) involves distant metastasis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q52
  {q:'Vulvar carcinoma invading the upper urethra or rectal mucosa corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IIIB','Stage IVA','Stage III','Stage IVB'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage IVA vulvar carcinoma involves invasion of upper urethral mucosa, bladder mucosa, rectal mucosa, or fixation to bone, distinguishing Stage IVA from lower urethral or perineal involvement.<br><br>Invasion of the upper, not just lower, urethra or rectal mucosa distinguishes Stage IVA from Stage II, which only involves lower urethral or perineal skin without mucosal invasion.<br><br>Stage IIIB (A) and III (C) involve nodal disease but not mucosal invasion of adjacent organs; Stage IVB (D) is distant metastasis beyond the pelvis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q53
  {q:'Vaginal carcinoma confined to the vaginal wall without extension outside is classified as:',
  o:['Stage I','Stage II','Stage III','Stage IVA'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage I vaginal carcinoma is tumour confined to the vaginal wall without extension to the subvaginal tissues or pelvic structures.<br><br>Staging of vaginal cancer uses the FIGO system, and the rare finding of Stage I disease reflects the fact that most vaginal carcinomas present at an advanced stage.<br><br>Stage II (B) involves subvaginal tissue extension; Stage III (C) reaches the pelvic wall; Stage IVA (D) involves bladder or rectal mucosal invasion.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q54
  {q:'Vaginal carcinoma extending to subvaginal tissues but not reaching pelvic wall corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage I','Stage II','Stage III','Stage IVA'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage II vaginal carcinoma involves extension into subvaginal tissues without reaching the pelvic sidewall Treatment combines external beam radiotherapy and brachytherapy.<br><br>Treatment requires combined external beam radiotherapy and intracavitary brachytherapy to cover the paravaginal extension. Stage II disease carries a worse prognosis than Stage I but is still potentially curable with radiotherapy.<br><br>Stage I (A) is confined to the vaginal wall; Stage III (C) extends to the pelvic wall; Stage IVA (D) involves mucosal invasion of bladder or rectum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q55 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'Vaginal carcinoma extending to the pelvic wall is staged as:',
  o:['Stage II','Stage IVA','Stage III','Stage IVB'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage III vaginal carcinoma extends to the pelvic wall, carrying a substantially worse prognosis than Stages I and II and requiring extended-field chemoradiotherapy.<br><br>Pelvic wall involvement upgrades the tumour from Stage II regardless of adjacent organ status, requiring extended-field chemoradiotherapy. Stage III vaginal carcinoma is associated with a substantially worse prognosis than Stage I or II and requires extended-field chemoradiotherapy to cover the pelvic sidewall involvement.<br><br>Stage II (A) extends into subvaginal tissues only; Stage IVA (B) involves bladder or rectal mucosal invasion; Stage IVB (D) involves distant metastasis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q56 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'Vaginal carcinoma invading bladder or rectal mucosa corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage IVA','Stage III','Stage IVB','Stage II'],a:0,
  e:`FIGO Stage IVA vaginal carcinoma involves invasion of the bladder mucosa or rectal mucosa: mucosal organ invasion distinguishes Stage IVA from Stage III pelvic wall involvement, and requires cystoscopic or sigmoidoscopic biopsy confirmation to distinguish from extrinsic compression.<br><br>Stage IVA vaginal carcinoma is managed with combined chemoradiotherapy; pelvic exenteration may be considered in highly selected cases.<br><br>Stage III (B) involves pelvic wall extension without mucosal invasion; Stage IVB (C) involves distant metastasis; Stage II (D) is subvaginal tissue only.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q57
  {q:'A patient with gestational trophoblastic neoplasia has lung metastases only. What stage according to FIGO?',
  o:['Stage I','Stage II','Stage IV','Stage III'],a:3,
  e:`FIGO Stage III gestational trophoblastic neoplasia (GTN) involves metastasis to the lungs only : whether from hydatidiform mole, choriocarcinoma or other GTN.<br><br>Lung metastases are the most common site of spread and define Stage III regardless of uterine disease extent or hCG level.<br><br>Stage I (A) is confined to the uterus; Stage II (B) extends to genital structures; Stage IV (D) involves non-pulmonary distant sites including liver or brain.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q58
  {q:'Gestational trophoblastic neoplasia confined to the uterus is staged as:',
  o:['Stage II','Stage III','Stage I','Stage IV'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage I gestational trophoblastic neoplasia is disease confined to the uterine corpus, with cure rates exceeding 90% using single-agent chemotherapy.<br><br>Stage I GTN carries an excellent prognosis, curable with single-agent methotrexate or actinomycin D, with hysterectomy reserved for chemotherapy-resistant cases. Regular hCG monitoring is the cornerstone of both diagnosis and treatment monitoring in GTN.<br><br>Stage II (A) extends to genital structures beyond the uterus; Stage III (B) involves lung metastases; Stage IV (D) involves non-pulmonary distant metastases.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q59
  {q:'Gestational trophoblastic neoplasia extending to genital structures such as vagina corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage I','Stage II','Stage III','Stage IV'],a:1,
  e:`FIGO Stage II gestational trophoblastic neoplasia involves spread to genital structures, including the vagina, ovaries, broad ligament or fallopian tubes, beyond the uterus but without distant metastasis.<br><br>Stage II GTN still carries an excellent prognosis with combination chemotherapy, with cure rates well above 90%. hCG monitoring remains the primary tool for tracking disease response, with normalisation of hCG confirming remission.<br><br>Stage I (A) is confined to the uterus; Stage III (C) involves lung metastases; Stage IV (D) involves liver, brain or other non-pulmonary distant sites.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q60
  {q:'Gestational trophoblastic neoplasia with metastases to liver or brain corresponds to:',
  o:['Stage II','Stage III','Stage IV','Stage IIIB'],a:2,
  e:`FIGO Stage IV gestational trophoblastic neoplasia involves metastases to non-pulmonary sites : liver, brain, kidney or gastrointestinal tract, including liver, brain, kidney or gastrointestinal tract.<br><br>Stage IV GTN represents the highest risk category with the lowest cure rates (70–80%) and requires intensive multi-agent chemotherapy, including regimens such as EMA-CO (etoposide, methotrexate, actinomycin D, cyclophosphamide, vincristine). brain metastases additionally require intrathecal methotrexate or whole-brain radiotherapy.<br><br>Stage II (A) involves genital extension; Stage III (B) involves pulmonary metastases only; Stage IIIB (D) is not a recognised FIGO substage for GTN.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q61 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'Implantation of the blastocyst normally occurs at approximately which time after fertilization?',
  o:['Day 2-3','Day 6-7','Day 4-5','Day 10-12'],a:1,
  e:`The blastocyst normally implants into the secretory endometrium at approximately day 6–7 after fertilization, after travelling along the fallopian tube as a cleaving morula.<br><br>The zygote undergoes cleavage divisions along the fallopian tube, reaching the uterine cavity as a blastocyst by day 4–5 before implantation begins. Implantation most commonly occurs on the posterior wall of the fundus and requires synchrony between the blastocyst and the endometrial window of implantation driven by progesterone.<br><br>Day 2–3 (A) is when the embryo is still in the fallopian tube as a morula; day 4–5 (C) is arrival in the uterine cavity; day 10–12 (D) is too late for normal implantation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q62
  {q:'The most common site of implantation in ectopic pregnancy is:',
  o:['Ampulla of fallopian tube','Isthmus of fallopian tube','Ovary','Cervix'],a:0,
  e:`The ampulla of the fallopian tube is the most common site of ectopic implantation, accounting for approximately 70–80% of all ectopic pregnancies.<br><br>Previous ectopic pregnancy increases the risk of recurrence to approximately 1 in 10, and all women with a previous ectopic should be offered an early ultrasound scan.<br><br>The isthmus (B) accounts for approximately 12%; the ovary (C) and cervix (D) are rare sites, each accounting for less than 1% of ectopic pregnancies.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},
// Q63
  {q:'A 28-year-old woman presents with amenorrhea, abdominal pain, and vaginal bleeding with a positive pregnancy test but empty uterus on ultrasound. What is the most likely diagnosis?',
  o:['Threatened miscarriage','Ectopic pregnancy','Complete miscarriage','Implantation bleeding'],a:1,
  e:`The combination of amenorrhea, abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding and a positive pregnancy test with an empty uterus on ultrasound is the classic presentation of ectopic pregnancy until proven otherwise.<br><br>The absence of an intrauterine gestational sac on transvaginal ultrasound in a woman with a positive hCG is the critical finding that mandates urgent assessment and serial hCG monitoring to confirm or exclude ectopic implantation.<br><br>Threatened miscarriage (A) has a closed cervix with intrauterine sac; complete miscarriage (C) has an empty uterus but falling hCG; implantation bleeding (D) is painless and very early.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},
// Q64
  {q:'The most common cause of first-trimester miscarriage is:',
  o:['Uterine anomalies','Hormonal deficiency','Chromosomal abnormalities','Antiphospholipid syndrome'],a:2,
  e:`Chromosomal abnormalities are the most common cause of first-trimester miscarriage, accounting for approximately 50–60% of all sporadic early pregnancy losses.<br><br>The high frequency of chromosomal abnormalities in sporadic miscarriage explains why recurrence risk after a single miscarriage is relatively low and most subsequent pregnancies are successful.<br><br>Uterine anomalies (A), hormonal deficiency (B) and antiphospholipid syndrome (D) are more commonly associated with recurrent miscarriage rather than sporadic first-trimester loss.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q65
  {q:'A patient presents with vaginal bleeding at 10 weeks of pregnancy. Cervix is closed and fetal heartbeat is present on ultrasound. What is the diagnosis?',
  o:['Threatened miscarriage','Inevitable miscarriage','Missed miscarriage','Ectopic pregnancy'],a:0,
  e:`Threatened miscarriage is defined as vaginal bleeding in early pregnancy with a closed cervical os and viable intrauterine pregnancy confirmed on ultrasound.<br><br>Management is expectant with advice to report any increase in bleeding or pain; routine progesterone supplementation is not recommended in most guidelines unless in specific risk groups.<br><br>Inevitable miscarriage (B) has an open cervical os; missed miscarriage (C) has no fetal heartbeat; ectopic pregnancy (D) has no intrauterine sac.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q66
  {q:'Vaginal bleeding with open cervical os and inevitable expulsion of products of conception. What type of miscarriage?',
  o:['Threatened miscarriage','Incomplete miscarriage','Inevitable miscarriage','Missed miscarriage'],a:2,
  e:`Inevitable miscarriage is defined by vaginal bleeding with an open or dilating cervical os : indicating that the process of expulsion has been initiated and cannot be reversed.<br><br>Unlike threatened miscarriage where the cervix remains closed, an open cervical os in early pregnancy confirms that spontaneous expulsion is underway and the pregnancy cannot be saved.<br><br>Threatened miscarriage (A) has a closed cervix; incomplete miscarriage (B) has partial expulsion already occurred; missed miscarriage (D) has no fetal heartbeat but a closed cervix.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q67
  {q:'A woman presents with vaginal bleeding and partial passage of products of conception with open cervical os. What type of miscarriage?',
  o:['Threatened miscarriage','Incomplete miscarriage','Missed miscarriage','Complete miscarriage'],a:1,
  e:`Incomplete miscarriage is defined as partial expulsion of the products of conception, with some tissue retained within the uterus, accompanied by an open cervical os and ongoing vaginal bleeding.<br><br>The retained products maintain an open cervix and continue to bleed, distinguishing it from complete miscarriage where all products have been passed and the cervix begins to close.<br><br>Threatened miscarriage (A) has closed cervix and viable pregnancy; missed miscarriage (C) has no fetal heartbeat with closed cervix; complete miscarriage (D) has complete expulsion with closing cervix.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q68 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'A patient has fetal death but products of conception remain in uterus for several weeks. What is this type of miscarriage?',
  o:['Threatened miscarriage','Septic miscarriage','Missed miscarriage','Inevitable miscarriage'],a:2,
  e:`Missed miscarriage (also called early fetal demise or silent miscarriage) is the death of the embryo or fetus with retention of the products of conception within the uterus.<br><br>Often without any bleeding or pain: it is typically diagnosed incidentally on routine first-trimester ultrasound when the expected fetal heartbeat is absent or when the gestational sac is empty (blighted ovum).<br><br>Threatened miscarriage (A) has a viable fetus; septic miscarriage (B) involves infection; inevitable miscarriage (D) has an open cervical os with active expulsion.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q69 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'Recurrent miscarriage is defined as:',
  o:['Three or more consecutive pregnancy losses','Two or more consecutive pregnancy losses','Two pregnancy losses at any time','Four consecutive miscarriages'],a:0,
  e:`Recurrent miscarriage is defined as three or more consecutive pregnancy losses before 24 weeks of gestation, the threshold used to trigger formal investigation.<br><br>Despite thorough investigation, a cause is found in only approximately 50% of couples; the remaining 50% have unexplained recurrent miscarriage but still have a good prognosis with supportive care.<br><br>Two consecutive losses (B) meets some definitions but the standard clinical definition remains three or more; non-consecutive losses (C) and four losses (D) are not the standard definition.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q70 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'Which chromosomal abnormality is most commonly associated with early spontaneous miscarriage?',
  o:['Trisomy 21','Turner syndrome','Triploidy','Trisomy 16'],a:3,
  e:`Trisomy 16 is the most common specific chromosomal abnormality found in early spontaneous miscarriage : incompatible with survival, it is virtually always found in first-trimester losses and is never seen in liveborn infants.<br><br>Chromosomal abnormalities overall account for approximately 50–60% of all first-trimester miscarriages, with autosomal trisomies being the most frequent class of abnormality. the high frequency of trisomy 16 reflects meiotic errors occurring predominantly during oogenesis in older eggs.<br><br>Trisomy 21 (A) is the most common viable trisomy; Turner syndrome (B) (45,X) can be found in miscarriage but less commonly than trisomy 16; triploidy (C) causes partial molar pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q71
  {q:'The most sensitive test for early detection of pregnancy is measurement of:',
  o:['Urinary hCG','Serum progesterone','Serum β-hCG','Pelvic ultrasound'],a:2,
  e:`Serum β-hCG (beta human chorionic gonadotropin) is the most sensitive test for early pregnancy detection, measurable in serum as early as 8–10 days after conception.<br><br>Before a missed period: β-hCG is produced by the syncytiotrophoblast of the implanting blastocyst and doubles approximately every 48 hours in a normal intrauterine pregnancy during the first trimester.<br><br>Urinary hCG (A) is less sensitive than serum; serum progesterone (B) confirms corpus luteum function but is less specific; pelvic ultrasound (D) cannot confirm pregnancy until 4–5 weeks gestation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q72
  {q:'In ectopic pregnancy, the classical triad includes amenorrhea, abdominal pain, and:',
  o:['Fever','Vaginal bleeding','Nausea and vomiting','Diarrhea'],a:1,
  e:`The classical triad of ectopic pregnancy is amenorrhea, abdominal pain and vaginal bleeding: this triad is present in approximately 50% of women with ectopic pregnancy at presentation.<br><br>Abdominal pain from tubal distension or haemorrhage, amenorrhea from early pregnancy, and vaginal bleeding from decidual breakdown as hCG production declines in the failing ectopic.<br><br>Fever (A) suggests infection; nausea (C) is a non-specific pregnancy symptom; diarrhoea (D) is not part of the classical ectopic triad.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q73 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'The most serious complication of ectopic pregnancy is:',
  o:['Hemorrhagic shock','Infertility','Pelvic infection','Chronic pelvic pain'],a:0,
  e:`Haemorrhagic shock from tubal rupture is the most immediately life-threatening complication of ectopic pregnancy : it remains a leading cause of maternal mortality in the first trimester worldwide.<br><br>When the ectopic pregnancy ruptures through the fallopian tube wall, rapid intraperitoneal haemorrhage occurs, causing acute haemoperitoneum and cardiovascular collapse if not rapidly treated. prompt surgical intervention, laparoscopic salpingectomy, is life-saving; intravenous access, fluid resuscitation and blood must be immediately available.<br><br>Infertility (B), pelvic infection (C) and chronic pelvic pain (D) are all recognised long-term sequelae but are not immediately life-threatening.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},
// Q74
  {q:'The most common risk factor for ectopic pregnancy is:',
  o:['Previous ectopic pregnancy','Pelvic inflammatory disease','IUD use','Endometriosis'],a:1,
  e:`Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), most commonly caused by Chlamydia trachomatis or Neisseria gonorrhoeae, is the most common risk factor for ectopic pregnancy, as tubal inflammation and scarring impairs the ciliary transport mechanism that moves the embryo towards the uterus.<br><br>PID-related peritubal adhesions and intraluminal scarring are the primary mechanisms that predispose to tubal implantation. previous ectopic pregnancy also significantly increases risk, with a recurrence rate of approximately 1 in 10.<br><br>Previous ectopic (A), IUD use (C) and endometriosis (D) are all established risk factors but are less prevalent than PID in the population as causes of ectopic pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},
// Q75
  {q:'A patient with ectopic pregnancy is hemodynamically stable and β-hCG levels are falling. What is the management?',
  o:['Emergency laparotomy','Methotrexate therapy','Expectant management','Laparoscopic salpingectomy'],a:2,
  e:`Expectant management is appropriate for a haemodynamically stable patient with an ectopic pregnancy and falling β-hCG levels, indicating spontaneous resolution without pharmacological intervention.<br><br>Indicating that the ectopic is naturally resolving without pharmacological or surgical intervention: criteria for expectant management typically include hCG below 1,000–1,500 IU/L, absence of fetal heartbeat, adnexal mass less than 35 mm and haemodynamic stability with no evidence of intraperitoneal bleeding.<br><br>Emergency laparotomy (A) is for ruptured ectopic with haemodynamic compromise; methotrexate (B) is for stable patients with hCG typically below 5,000 IU/L but still rising or plateaued; laparoscopic salpingectomy (D) is surgical treatment for stable or unstable patients not suitable for expectant or medical management.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q76
  {q:'In gestational trophoblastic disease, the most common form is:',
  o:['Hydatidiform mole','Choriocarcinoma','Invasive mole','Placental site trophoblastic tumour'],a:0,
  e:`Hydatidiform mole, either complete or partial, is the most common form of gestational trophoblastic disease, presenting with abnormal proliferation of trophoblastic tissue and characteristic hydropic degeneration of chorionic villi.<br><br>Complete moles are diploid (46XX or 46XY) of entirely paternal origin, while partial moles are triploid (69XXX or 69XXY) with one maternal and two paternal haploid sets. hydatidiform moles require uterine evacuation followed by regular hCG monitoring to detect persistent trophoblastic disease or malignant transformation.<br><br>Choriocarcinoma (B) is the most malignant but least common form; invasive mole (C) is a post-molar complication; placental site trophoblastic tumour (D) is the rarest form.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q77
  {q:'Complete hydatidiform mole usually has which karyotype?',
  o:['69XXX','69XXY','46XX paternal origin','46XY maternal and paternal'],a:2,
  e:`Complete hydatidiform mole most commonly has a 46XX karyotype of entirely androgenetic (paternal) origin : arising from fertilization of an empty (anucleate) egg by a single haploid sperm that then duplicates its genome.<br><br>The maternal genome is entirely absent, resulting in abnormal trophoblastic proliferation without fetal tissue and the characteristic snowstorm appearance on ultrasound. the purely paternal genome explains the absence of fetal parts and the high proliferative capacity of complete mole compared to partial mole.<br><br>69XXX (A) is the karyotype of partial mole; 69XXY (B) is another partial mole karyotype; 46XY maternal and paternal (D) is incorrect as complete mole has no maternal contribution.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q78
  {q:'Partial hydatidiform mole most commonly has which karyotype?',
  o:['46XX','69XXX','46XY','46XX paternal origin'],a:1,
  e:`Partial hydatidiform mole most commonly has a 69XXX triploid karyotype : arising from fertilization of a normal haploid egg by two sperms (or one sperm that duplicates).<br><br>Partial moles contain one maternal and two paternal haploid genomes, resulting in the presence of some fetal tissue (often abnormal), partial hydropic change of the placenta and an identifiable fetal or embryonic structure distinguishing them from complete moles.<br><br>46XX (A) is the complete mole karyotype; 46XY (C) is normal male; 46XX paternal origin (D) describes the androgenetic complete mole specifically.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q79 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'The most common presenting symptom of molar pregnancy is:',
  o:['Severe abdominal pain','Hypertension','Vaginal bleeding in early pregnancy','Fever'],a:2,
  e:`Vaginal bleeding in early pregnancy is the most common presenting symptom of molar pregnancy, occurring in approximately 90% of cases.<br><br>The bleeding arises from haemorrhage into the hydropic villous tissue and separation of the degenerating placenta from the uterine wall, typically presenting in the first trimester with uterine size larger than expected for gestational age.<br><br>Severe abdominal pain (A) is not the hallmark presentation; hypertension (B) may develop with complete mole but is not the most common presenting symptom; fever (D) suggests infection, not molar pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q80
  {q:'Ultrasound appearance of complete molar pregnancy typically shows:',
  o:['Snowstorm appearance','Empty gestational sac','Twin pregnancy','Normal placenta'],a:0,
  e:`The classic ultrasound appearance of complete hydatidiform mole is the "snowstorm" pattern : a uterus filled with a heterogeneous echogenic mass with multiple small anechoic spaces representing the hydropic chorionic villi.<br><br>Modern high-resolution transvaginal ultrasound has improved molar pregnancy detection in the first trimester, where the classic snowstorm appearance may be less pronounced than in second-trimester presentations.<br><br>Empty gestational sac (B) is a blighted ovum (anembryonic pregnancy); twin pregnancy (C) is a separate diagnosis; normal placenta (D) is incompatible with complete molar pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q81 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A patient with molar pregnancy has very high β-hCG levels. Which complication is most likely?',
  o:['Hypothyroidism','Diabetes','Hypocalcemia','Hyperthyroidism'],a:3,
  e:`Hyperthyroidism is the complication most associated with very high β-hCG levels in molar pregnancy: hCG shares structural homology with TSH (thyroid-stimulating hormone) and cross-reacts with TSH receptors on thyrocytes.<br><br>Extremely elevated hCG in complete molar pregnancy can stimulate the thyroid gland sufficiently to produce clinical or biochemical hyperthyroidism, sometimes severe enough to cause thyroid storm.<br><br>Hypothyroidism (A) is not caused by elevated hCG; diabetes (B) and hypocalcaemia (C) are not complications of molar pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q82
  {q:'The most malignant form of gestational trophoblastic disease is:',
  o:['Invasive mole','Partial hydatidiform mole','Choriocarcinoma','Placental site trophoblastic tumour'],a:2,
  e:`Choriocarcinoma is the most malignant form of gestational trophoblastic disease : it is a highly aggressive tumour of trophoblastic cells that invades blood vessels early, leading to widespread haematogenous metastases particularly to the lung, brain and liver.<br><br>Despite its aggressiveness, choriocarcinoma is highly chemosensitive and the majority of patients, even with metastatic disease, are cured with platinum-based combination chemotherapy. choriocarcinoma may arise after any type of pregnancy : molar, ectopic, miscarriage or term delivery.<br><br>Invasive mole (A) is locally invasive but rarely metastasises; partial mole (B) has the lowest malignant potential; placental site trophoblastic tumour (D) is rare and less responsive to chemotherapy.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q83 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'The most common site of metastasis in choriocarcinoma is:',
  o:['Brain','Lung','Liver','Kidney'],a:1,
  e:`The lung is the most common site of metastasis in choriocarcinoma, occurring in approximately 80% of patients with metastatic gestational trophoblastic neoplasia.<br><br>Haematogenous spread via pulmonary circulation results in multiple discrete pulmonary nodules visible on chest X-ray or CT, which often regress dramatically with chemotherapy confirming the diagnosis in conjunction with elevated hCG.<br><br>Brain (A) and liver (C) are Stage IV metastatic sites with worse prognosis; kidney (D) is an uncommon site of choriocarcinoma spread.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q84
  {q:'Intrauterine fetal death (IUFD) refers to fetal death occurring after:',
  o:['12 weeks','16 weeks','20 weeks','24 weeks'],a:2,
  e:`Intrauterine fetal death (IUFD) is defined as death of the fetus occurring at or after 20 weeks of gestation, distinguishing it from miscarriage which applies below 20 weeks.<br><br>After IUFD, the longer the fetus remains in utero, the greater the risk of maternal coagulopathy from thromboplastin release into the maternal circulation : a recognised and serious complication.<br><br>Deaths before 12 weeks (A) and 16 weeks (B) are classified as early miscarriages; death after 24 weeks (D) is used as the stillbirth threshold in some countries including the UK.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q85
  {q:'The most common cause of intrauterine fetal death in developed countries is:',
  o:['Congenital anomalies','Placental insufficiency','Umbilical cord accident','Infection'],a:1,
  e:`Placental insufficiency, including chronic uteroplacental insufficiency from pre-eclampsia, hypertension, diabetes and antiphospholipid syndrome, is the most common identifiable cause of intrauterine fetal death (IUFD) in developed countries.<br><br>Inadequate placental transfer of oxygen and nutrients leads to progressive fetal compromise, acidosis and ultimately fetal death, often preceded by fetal growth restriction and abnormal Doppler findings.<br><br>Congenital anomalies (A) are the second most common cause; umbilical cord accidents (C) and infections (D) are less common causes in developed-country populations.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q86 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'Ultrasound sign most consistent with IUFD is:',
  o:['Macrosomia','Polyhydramnios','Ventriculomegaly','Absence of fetal cardiac activity'],a:3,
  e:`Absence of fetal cardiac activity on real-time ultrasound is the definitive diagnostic criterion for intrauterine fetal death, which must be confirmed by a second operator before diagnosis.<br><br>The Spalding sign (overlapping fetal skull bones) and other radiological signs are late changes relevant to plain X-ray in remote settings rather than the primary diagnostic approach.<br><br>Macrosomia (A), polyhydramnios (B) and ventriculomegaly (C) may coexist with a live fetus and are not consistent with IUFD.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q87 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'The Spalding sign in IUFD refers to:',
  o:['Absent fetal heartbeat','Hyperechoic fetal bowel','Overlapping fetal skull bones','Gas in fetal vessels'],a:2,
  e:`The Spalding sign refers to the overlapping of fetal skull bones seen on X-ray or ultrasound following intrauterine fetal death.<br><br>While the Spalding sign is a recognised radiological indicator of IUFD, modern practice relies on absence of fetal cardiac activity on ultrasound as the primary diagnostic criterion.<br><br>Absent fetal heartbeat (A) is the primary diagnostic sign on ultrasound; hyperechoic bowel (B) is associated with Down syndrome or infection in a live fetus; gas in fetal vessels (D) is a very late post-mortem change.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q88
  {q:'In IUFD, coagulopathy can develop due to release of:',
  o:['Fibrinogen','Thromboplastin','Prostaglandins','Oxytocin'],a:1,
  e:`Coagulopathy following IUFD results from the release of thromboplastin (tissue factor) from the degenerating placenta and fetal tissues into the maternal circulation.<br><br>This triggers disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) through consumption of clotting factors and platelets : the risk increases progressively the longer the dead fetus remains in utero and is significant after approximately 3–4 weeks of retention.<br><br>Fibrinogen (A) is consumed in DIC rather than causing it; prostaglandins (C) initiate uterine contractions; oxytocin (D) stimulates uterine contractions but does not cause coagulopathy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q89
  {q:'Intrauterine growth restriction (IUGR) is defined as fetal weight below:',
  o:['3rd percentile','5th percentile','10th percentile','15th percentile'],a:2,
  e:`IUGR is conventionally defined as estimated fetal weight below the 10th percentile for gestational age: this threshold is the most widely used clinical definition, although small-for-gestational-age (SGA) fetuses below the 10th percentile may include constitutionally small but normally grown fetuses.<br><br>The 3rd percentile is used to identify the most severely affected fetuses at highest risk of perinatal morbidity. the distinction between IUGR and constitutional smallness requires Doppler assessment, serial growth measurements and assessment of amniotic fluid volume.<br><br>3rd percentile (A) identifies severe IUGR specifically; 5th percentile (B) is used in some definitions but not the standard threshold; 15th percentile (D) is not a recognised clinical threshold.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q90 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'The most common cause of IUGR worldwide is:',
  o:['Chromosomal abnormalities','Multiple pregnancy','Maternal infection','Maternal hypertension'],a:3,
  e:`Maternal hypertension, including pre-eclampsia, chronic hypertension and hypertensive disorders of pregnancy, is the most common cause of IUGR worldwide, through failure of trophoblastic invasion of spiral arteries.<br><br>The underlying mechanism is failure of normal trophoblastic invasion of spiral arteries, which results in reduced uteroplacental blood flow, placental insufficiency and restricted fetal growth. risk factors for IUGR associated with pre-eclampsia include nulliparity, advanced maternal age, autoimmune disease, diabetes and antiphospholipid syndrome.<br><br>Chromosomal abnormalities (A) cause symmetrical IUGR; multiple pregnancy (B) is associated with IUGR particularly in monochorionic twins; maternal infection (C) causes IUGR less commonly than hypertension.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q91 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'Symmetrical IUGR usually occurs due to:',
  o:['Placental insufficiency','Maternal hypertension','Early fetal insult','Cord compression'],a:2,
  e:`Symmetrical IUGR, characterised by proportionate reduction of both head and abdominal circumference, results from an early global insult to the fetus, typically occurring in the first trimester when all organs are growing at the same rate.<br><br>Common causes include chromosomal abnormalities, early intrauterine infections (TORCH), severe maternal malnutrition and teratogen exposure, all of which affect cell number from the outset. the proportionate reduction in all biometric parameters distinguishes symmetrical from asymmetrical IUGR, which is a later-onset, nutrition-sparing pattern.<br><br>Placental insufficiency (A) and maternal hypertension (B) typically cause asymmetrical IUGR through late-onset nutrient restriction; cord compression (D) causes acute fetal compromise rather than chronic growth restriction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q92 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'Asymmetrical IUGR is characterized by:',
  o:['Normal head size with reduced abdominal circumference','Reduced head with normal abdomen','Proportionate reduction of all parameters','Normal biparietal diameter and femur length'],a:0,
  e:`Asymmetrical IUGR is characterised by a disproportionately reduced abdominal circumference relative to a relatively preserved head circumference, reflecting the brain-sparing effect of uteroplacental insufficiency.<br><br>Reflecting the "brain-sparing" effect: when placental insufficiency reduces nutrient delivery in the third trimester, the fetus preferentially redistributes blood to the brain, heart and adrenal glands at the expense of the liver and abdominal viscera, resulting in a reduced abdominal circumference as the liver glycogen stores are depleted.<br><br>Reduced head with normal abdomen (B) is not a recognised IUGR pattern; proportionate reduction (C) is symmetrical IUGR; normal BPD and femur length (D) is consistent with asymmetrical IUGR but incomplete as a description.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q93
  {q:'The most useful ultrasound parameter to detect IUGR is:',
  o:['Biparietal diameter','Head circumference','Abdominal circumference','Femur length'],a:2,
  e:`The abdominal circumference (AC) is the most sensitive single ultrasound parameter for detecting IUGR, as it reflects fetal liver size and glycogen storage.<br><br>The first reserve to be depleted when placental nutrient delivery is impaired: a reduced AC is the earliest and most significant marker of asymmetrical IUGR, falling below the expected centile before head circumference or femur length are affected.<br><br>Biparietal diameter (A) and head circumference (B) are preserved in asymmetrical IUGR due to brain-sparing; femur length (D) is the last parameter affected.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q94
  {q:'Doppler study in IUGR commonly shows increased resistance in:',
  o:['Umbilical artery','Middle cerebral artery','Ductus venosus','Uterine artery'],a:0,
  e:`Umbilical artery Doppler showing increased resistance, elevated systolic-diastolic ratio, absent or reversed end-diastolic flow, is the hallmark Doppler finding of IUGR.<br><br>As placental vascular resistance increases due to obliteration of tertiary stem villi, umbilical arterial blood flow is progressively impaired, first showing elevated resistance, then absent end-diastolic flow and finally reversed end-diastolic flow : each step indicating worsening fetal compromise.<br><br>Middle cerebral artery (B) shows decreased resistance in brain-sparing; ductus venosus (C) and uterine artery (D) are secondary Doppler assessments providing additional prognostic information.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q95
  {q:'Brain-sparing effect in IUGR refers to:',
  o:['Increased intracranial pressure','Increased blood flow to brain','Decreased oxygen consumption by brain','Microcephaly development'],a:1,
  e:`Brain-sparing in IUGR refers to the fetal redistribution of cardiac output that preferentially increases blood flow to the brain, heart and adrenal glands at the expense of peripheral organs including the liver, gut and kidneys.<br><br>The cerebroplacental ratio (CPR = MCA PI / umbilical artery PI) is used clinically to quantify the degree of brain-sparing and helps guide timing of delivery.<br><br>Increased intracranial pressure (A) is not the mechanism; decreased oxygen consumption (C) does not occur : the brain remains metabolically active; microcephaly (D) indicates symmetrical IUGR from early insult rather than brain-sparing.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q96
  {q:'Which maternal habit significantly increases risk of IUGR?',
  o:['Smoking','Alcohol use','Caffeine intake','Exercise'],a:0,
  e:`Maternal smoking is the most important modifiable risk factor for IUGR: nicotine causes uteroplacental vasoconstriction, reducing placental blood flow and nutrient delivery, while carbon monoxide reduces fetal oxygen-carrying capacity by forming carboxyhaemoglobin.<br><br>Together these mechanisms produce dose-dependent fetal growth restriction. smoking is responsible for approximately 20–30% of low-birthweight deliveries in developed countries and is the single most preventable cause of IUGR.<br><br>Alcohol use (B) causes fetal alcohol syndrome and growth restriction but is less common than smoking as a cause of IUGR; caffeine (C) at high doses has a modest effect; moderate exercise (D) does not increase IUGR risk.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q97
  {q:'A fetus with severe IUGR is at highest risk of:',
  o:['Post-term pregnancy','Macrosomia','Perinatal asphyxia','Both perinatal asphyxia and stillbirth'],a:3,
  e:`Severe IUGR, particularly with absent or reversed end-diastolic flow in the umbilical artery, places the fetus at highest risk of both perinatal asphyxia and stillbirth.<br><br>Chronic uteroplacental insufficiency leads to progressive fetal acidosis, and the critically compromised fetus can decompensate rapidly, resulting in either acute intrapartum asphyxia or intrauterine death before labour.<br><br>Post-term pregnancy (A) and macrosomia (B) are associated with the opposite of growth restriction; perinatal asphyxia alone (C) is correct but incomplete : stillbirth risk is equally important in severe IUGR.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q98
  {q:'The most common placental pathology associated with IUGR is:',
  o:['Placental infarction','Placenta previa','Vasa previa','Placental abruption'],a:0,
  e:`Placental infarction, areas of ischaemic necrosis resulting from uteroplacental vascular insufficiency, is the most common placental pathology associated with IUGR.<br><br>Placental infarcts confined to the periphery and involving less than 5% of the placenta are common and of no clinical significance; extensive central infarction is pathological.<br><br>Placenta previa (B) causes antepartum haemorrhage but not IUGR; vasa previa (C) is a vessel location anomaly; placental abruption (D) causes acute fetal distress rather than chronic growth restriction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q99
  {q:'A woman with previous molar pregnancy should avoid pregnancy for at least:',
  o:['3 months','6 months','1 year','2 years'],a:2,
  e:`After successful treatment of a hydatidiform mole with normalisation of β-hCG, women are advised to avoid pregnancy for at least 1 year.<br><br>This recommendation ensures that hCG monitoring can reliably distinguish a new pregnancy from persistent or recurrent trophoblastic disease, as a rising hCG could indicate either a new pregnancy or malignant GTN : making them impossible to distinguish clinically without the waiting period.<br><br>3 months (A) and 6 months (B) are insufficient monitoring periods; 2 years (D) exceeds current guideline recommendations for uncomplicated molar pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q100 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'Persistent elevation of β-hCG after evacuation of molar pregnancy suggests:',
  o:['Normal post-molar course','New intrauterine pregnancy','Ovarian hyperstimulation','Persistent trophoblastic disease'],a:3,
  e:`Persistent elevation of β-hCG after uterine evacuation of a hydatidiform mole indicates persistent gestational trophoblastic disease (pGTD), which occurs in approximately 15–20% of complete hydatidiform moles.<br><br>Regular hCG monitoring after molar evacuation is the cornerstone of surveillance; a plateau or rise in hCG after initial decline is the critical trigger for treatment.<br><br>Normal post-molar course (A) shows progressive hCG decline to undetectable; new pregnancy (B) must be excluded by contraception during monitoring; ovarian hyperstimulation (C) does not persist after molar evacuation.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q101 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'The most reliable method to diagnose ectopic pregnancy early is:',
  o:['Serum β-hCG alone','Pelvic examination','Serum β-hCG with transvaginal ultrasound','CT scan of pelvis'],a:2,
  e:`The combination of serum β-hCG measurement with transvaginal ultrasound is the most reliable method for early ectopic pregnancy diagnosis, combining early localisation with quantitative hCG assessment.<br><br>Transvaginal ultrasound can visualise an intrauterine gestational sac from approximately 4.5–5 weeks, and failure to identify an intrauterine sac with a β-hCG above the discriminatory zone (typically 1,000–2,000 IU/L) strongly suggests an ectopic or failing pregnancy.<br><br>Serum β-hCG alone (A) cannot localise the pregnancy; pelvic examination (B) may elicit adnexal tenderness but is non-diagnostic; CT scan (D) is not routinely used for ectopic pregnancy diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},
// Q102
  {q:'A patient with ruptured ectopic pregnancy most commonly presents with:',
  o:['Severe abdominal pain and shock','Mild pelvic discomfort only','Nausea and vomiting','Urinary frequency'],a:0,
  e:`Ruptured ectopic pregnancy presents with sudden severe lower abdominal pain followed rapidly by signs of haemorrhagic shock, hypotension, tachycardia, pallor and collapse, due to acute intraperitoneal haemorrhage.<br><br>The pain results from peritoneal irritation by haemoperitoneum and may radiate to the shoulder tip from subphrenic blood causing diaphragmatic irritation. ruptured ectopic pregnancy remains one of the most common causes of maternal death in the first trimester and requires immediate emergency laparoscopy or laparotomy.<br><br>Mild pelvic discomfort (B) is more consistent with an unruptured ectopic or threatened miscarriage; nausea (C) and urinary frequency (D) are non-specific pregnancy symptoms that do not suggest tubal rupture.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},
// Q103 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A patient with molar pregnancy develops very large uterus for gestational age. What is the most likely cause?',
  o:['Multiple pregnancy','Polyhydramnios','Normal uterine growth','Proliferation of trophoblastic tissue'],a:3,
  e:`Uterine size larger than expected for gestational age in molar pregnancy results from excessive proliferation of trophoblastic tissue and accumulation of hydropic chorionic villi filling the uterine cavity.<br><br>This is one of the clinical features that raises suspicion for complete molar pregnancy : the trophoblastic tissue proliferates far beyond what normal placenta would at the equivalent gestation.<br><br>Multiple pregnancy (A) can enlarge the uterus but less dramatically; polyhydramnios (B) is associated with molar pregnancy but is secondary; normal uterine growth (C) does not produce fundal height significantly larger than dates.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q104 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'Theca lutein cysts associated with molar pregnancy are caused by:',
  o:['Elevated β-hCG','Elevated progesterone','Uterine distension','Elevated AFP'],a:0,
  e:`Theca lutein cysts form in molar pregnancy because markedly elevated β-hCG cross-reacts with FSH and LH receptors on ovarian theca cells, stimulating excessive ovarian follicle development and luteinisation.<br><br>The resulting bilateral multilocular ovarian cysts may be large enough to cause adnexal pain or torsion and typically resolve spontaneously after molar evacuation and hCG normalisation.<br><br>Elevated progesterone (B) is produced by the theca lutein cysts rather than causing them; uterine distension (C) and elevated AFP (D) do not cause ovarian cyst formation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q105
  {q:'Which complication is commonly associated with molar pregnancy before 20 weeks?',
  o:['Gestational diabetes','Placenta previa','Vasa previa','Preeclampsia'],a:3,
  e:`Pre-eclampsia before 20 weeks of gestation is a classical and clinically important association with complete hydatidiform mole, occurring when very high hCG mimics TSH and drives endothelial dysfunction.<br><br>The very high trophoblastic mass in complete molar pregnancy produces exaggerated anti-angiogenic signalling and endothelial dysfunction, the same mechanism as pre-eclampsia in normal pregnancy, but occurring unusually early before 20 weeks when pre-eclampsia would not normally be expected.<br><br>Gestational diabetes (A), placenta previa (B) and vasa previa (C) are not recognised associations of molar pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Shaw's Textbook of Gynaecology)</em>`},
// Q106 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'The most common symptom of IUFD noticed by mother is:',
  o:['Abdominal pain','Vaginal bleeding','Loss of fetal movements','Fever'],a:2,
  e:`Cessation of fetal movements, loss of fetal movements, is the most common symptom noticed by the mother in intrauterine fetal death.<br><br>Mothers typically notice the absence of the fetal movements they had been monitoring in the third trimester, and this is often the first and only warning symptom before the diagnosis is confirmed on ultrasound.<br><br>Abdominal pain (A) may occur in abruption-related IUFD; vaginal bleeding (B) is not universal; fever (D) suggests infection but is not the most common presenting feature.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q107 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'The gold standard for confirming IUFD is:',
  o:['Ultrasound showing absent cardiac activity','Doppler showing absent flow','X-ray showing Spalding sign','CTG showing flat trace'],a:0,
  e:`Ultrasound demonstrating absent fetal cardiac activity is the gold standard for confirming intrauterine fetal death: real-time ultrasound visualisation showing no cardiac motion is definitive.<br><br>It must be confirmed by a second assessor and documented carefully before communicating the diagnosis to the parents. the absence of a fetal heartbeat should be observed for at least one minute by real-time scanning before confirming the diagnosis.<br><br>Doppler showing absent flow (B) requires cardiac activity assessment first; X-ray Spalding sign (C) is a late, non-specific radiological finding; CTG flat trace (D) cannot replace direct ultrasound cardiac visualisation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q108
  {q:'One important complication after IUFD if fetus retained for long is:',
  o:['Thyroid storm','DIC','Pulmonary embolism','Severe pre-eclampsia'],a:1,
  e:`Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) is a critical complication of prolonged fetal retention after IUFD: thromboplastin released from the degenerating placenta and fetal tissues enters the maternal circulation, triggering the coagulation cascade and consuming clotting factors and platelets.<br><br>The risk becomes clinically significant after approximately 3–4 weeks of retention, producing consumptive coagulopathy that can cause life-threatening haemorrhage. prompt delivery of the dead fetus, by induction of labour or surgical evacuation, is therefore recommended to minimise DIC risk.<br><br>Thyroid storm (A) is not a complication of IUFD; pulmonary embolism (C) risk exists in any pregnancy but is not specifically linked to IUFD retention; severe pre-eclampsia (D) may have caused the IUFD but is not a consequence of retention.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q109 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'The most common chromosomal abnormality associated with complete mole is:',
  o:['Triploidy 69XXX','Trisomy 21','Monosomy X','Diploid androgenetic genome'],a:3,
  e:`Complete hydatidiform mole characteristically has a diploid androgenetic genome : both sets of chromosomes are of paternal origin, arising from fertilization of an empty (anucleate) egg by a haploid sperm that then duplicates.<br><br>The most common karyotype is 46XX, entirely paternal, with absence of the maternal genome producing abnormal trophoblastic proliferation, no fetal tissue and no embryonic development. the androgenetic origin distinguishes complete mole from partial mole (which is triploid with one maternal set) and from normal diploidy.<br><br>Triploidy 69XXX (A) is the karyotype of partial mole; trisomy 21 (B) is Down syndrome; monosomy X (C) is Turner syndrome : neither causes molar pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q110 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'A partial mole usually contains:',
  o:['No fetal tissue','Only maternal chromosomes','Some fetal tissue','Completely normal placenta'],a:2,
  e:`A partial hydatidiform mole, unlike a complete mole, usually contains some fetal tissue (embryo or fetus), albeit typically abnormal, alongside partial hydropic villi and an identifiable placental component.<br><br>The presence of fetal tissue distinguishes partial from complete mole on both ultrasound and histology, though fetal tissue in partial moles is rarely viable and is typically severely growth-restricted.<br><br>No fetal tissue (A) defines complete mole; only maternal chromosomes (B) describes a completely different condition; completely normal placenta (D) is inconsistent with any molar pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q111 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'The most sensitive marker for monitoring treatment of trophoblastic disease is:',
  o:['β-hCG','Serum AFP','Serum LDH','Serum inhibin'],a:0,
  e:`Serum β-hCG is the most sensitive tumour marker for monitoring treatment of gestational trophoblastic disease, falling predictably with treatment and rising with recurrence.<br><br>Falling predictably with successful treatment and rising with recurrence: hCG is produced exclusively by trophoblastic tissue, making it a uniquely specific and sensitive marker that guides treatment decisions, confirms remission (when hCG normalises) and detects relapse before clinical signs appear.<br><br>AFP (B) is used for yolk sac tumours; LDH (C) is used for dysgerminomas; inhibin (D) is used for granulosa cell tumours : none are appropriate markers for trophoblastic disease surveillance.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q112 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A fetus with symmetrical IUGR usually has:',
  o:['Normal head with reduced abdomen','Enlarged head with small body','Reduced abdominal circumference only','Reduced head and abdominal size proportionately'],a:3,
  e:`Symmetrical IUGR is characterised by a proportionate reduction in both head and abdominal circumference : all biometric parameters are reduced equally.<br><br>The proportionate reduction means the abdominal circumference is not disproportionately reduced relative to the head, distinguishing it from asymmetrical IUGR where the AC falls out of proportion to a relatively preserved head circumference.<br><br>Normal head with reduced abdomen (A) and reduced abdominal circumference only (C) describe asymmetrical IUGR; enlarged head with small body (B) is not a recognised IUGR pattern.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q113 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'The most important determinant of fetal growth is:',
  o:['Maternal nutrition alone','Fetal genetic potential','Placental function','Fetal hormone levels'],a:2,
  e:`Placental function, specifically the efficiency of placental transfer of oxygen, glucose, amino acids and other nutrients, is the most important determinant of fetal growth.<br><br>The placenta acts as the interface between the maternal and fetal circulations, and any impairment in placental vascular development, surface area or transport capacity directly limits fetal growth regardless of adequate maternal nutrition.<br><br>Maternal nutrition (A) is important but less direct than placental function; fetal genetic potential (B) sets the ceiling but cannot be realised without adequate placental delivery; fetal hormones (D) respond to placental signals but do not primarily determine growth.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q114
  {q:'A fetus with asymmetrical IUGR usually develops during:',
  o:['Third trimester','First trimester','Second trimester','At birth'],a:0,
  e:`Asymmetrical IUGR characteristically develops in the third trimester when placental reserve is no longer sufficient to meet the rapidly increasing metabolic demands of the fetus.<br><br>Late-onset placental insufficiency, from progressive vascular disease associated with hypertension, pre-eclampsia or uteroplacental atherosclerosis, reduces nutrient delivery after the phase of normal growth, producing the asymmetrical pattern where head circumference is relatively spared at the expense of abdominal circumference.<br><br>First trimester (B) is the timing of symmetrical IUGR; second trimester (C) IUGR is less common; at birth (D) is not when IUGR develops : it is when the growth restriction is delivered.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q115
  {q:'The main pathological process in placental insufficiency leading to IUGR is:',
  o:['Increased fetal metabolic demand','Reduced uteroplacental blood flow','Maternal anaemia','Umbilical cord compression'],a:1,
  e:`Reduced uteroplacental blood flow is the primary pathological mechanism in placental insufficiency leading to IUGR: failure of normal trophoblastic invasion into the maternal spiral arteries in early pregnancy prevents the physiological transformation of these muscular vessels into large-calibre low-resistance channels.<br><br>The result is persistently high-resistance uteroplacental circulation, reduced placental perfusion, placental infarction and impaired fetal nutrition. this failure of spiral artery remodelling is also the mechanism underlying pre-eclampsia, which frequently coexists with IUGR.<br><br>Increased fetal metabolic demand (A) is a contributor in multifetal pregnancy; maternal anaemia (C) is a minor factor; umbilical cord compression (D) causes acute fetal distress rather than chronic IUGR.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q116 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'A major risk factor for miscarriage in early pregnancy is:',
  o:['Young maternal age','Paternal smoking','Advanced maternal age','Low BMI'],a:2,
  e:`Advanced maternal age is a major risk factor for early pregnancy loss : miscarriage risk increases substantially with maternal age, rising from approximately 10–15% in women under 35 to over 50% in women aged 45 and above.<br><br>This reflects the progressive decline in oocyte quality and the consequent increase in meiotic errors producing chromosomal abnormalities, particularly autosomal trisomies, which are the most common cause of first-trimester miscarriage.<br><br>Young maternal age (A) is associated with lower, not higher, miscarriage risk; paternal smoking (B) has a modest effect; low BMI (D) is not a major independent risk factor for miscarriage.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q117 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'Septic miscarriage most commonly occurs due to:',
  o:['Antiphospholipid syndrome','Uterine anomalies','Chromosomal abnormality','Unsafe abortion'],a:3,
  e:`Septic miscarriage most commonly results from unsafe or illegal abortion performed in non-sterile conditions, introducing bacteria directly into the uterine cavity.<br><br>Instrumentation of the uterus without aseptic technique allows bowel-derived organisms including Clostridium, E. coli and Bacteroides to infect the retained products of conception, potentially leading to life-threatening endometritis, septicaemia and septic shock.<br><br>Antiphospholipid syndrome (A) and uterine anomalies (B) cause recurrent miscarriage but not typically septic miscarriage; chromosomal abnormality (C) causes the miscarriage itself but not the sepsis : sepsis is a complication of unsafe management.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q118
  {q:'Which hormone maintains early pregnancy until placental function is established?',
  o:['Oestrogen from ovary','Progesterone from corpus luteum','hCG from pituitary','LH from anterior pituitary'],a:1,
  e:`Progesterone produced by the corpus luteum maintains the decidualised endometrium and uterine quiescence during early pregnancy until the placenta assumes steroidogenic function at approximately 8–10 weeks.<br><br>Without adequate corpus luteal progesterone, the decidua would shed and the pregnancy would fail : the rationale for progesterone supplementation in recurrent miscarriage and IVF cycles.<br><br>Oestrogen from the ovary (A) has a supporting role; hCG from the pituitary (C) is incorrect : hCG is produced by trophoblast, not pituitary; LH from the anterior pituitary (D) is what the corpus luteum responds to before pregnancy, but its role is replaced by hCG.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q119 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'Implantation occurs most commonly in which part of uterus?',
  o:['Anterior wall','Lower segment','Fundus/posterior wall','Cornual region'],a:2,
  e:`Implantation occurs most commonly in the posterior wall of the fundus, the upper posterior uterine cavity, where the endometrium has the most favourable conditions for blastocyst attachment and invasion.<br><br>The posterior fundal location is where the endometrial thickness is greatest, blood supply is most abundant and the window of implantation is most permissive for blastocyst invasion.<br><br>Anterior wall (A) is a common but not the most common site; lower segment (B) is associated with placenta previa; cornual region (D) is associated with interstitial ectopic pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q120 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'Failure of trophoblastic invasion into spiral arteries is a key mechanism in:',
  o:['IUGR','Ectopic pregnancy','Hydatidiform mole','Choriocarcinoma'],a:0,
  e:`Failure of normal trophoblastic invasion into the maternal spiral arteries, preventing their physiological transformation into large-calibre, low-resistance vessels, is the central mechanism of IUGR arising from placental insufficiency.<br><br>Without adequate remodelling of the spiral arteries, uteroplacental blood flow remains restricted, placental perfusion is reduced, and fetal nutrient and oxygen delivery is impaired throughout gestation. this same mechanism of inadequate trophoblast invasion also underlies pre-eclampsia, which frequently coexists with IUGR.<br><br>Ectopic pregnancy (B) involves implantation outside the uterus; hydatidiform mole (C) involves abnormal trophoblastic proliferation rather than failure of invasion; choriocarcinoma (D) is a malignant trophoblastic tumour with unrelated pathophysiology.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q121
  {q:'A 28-year-old woman develops heavy vaginal bleeding immediately after delivery of the placenta. What is the most likely cause?',
  o:['Cervical laceration','Retained placenta','Uterine atony','Coagulation defect'],a:2,
  e:`Uterine atony, failure of the uterus to contract adequately after placental delivery, is the most common cause of immediate postpartum haemorrhage, accounting for approximately 70–80% of all PPH cases.<br><br>Risk factors for uterine atony include macrosomia, multiple pregnancy, prolonged labour, oxytocin use, grand multiparity, polyhydramnios and antepartum haemorrhage : all conditions that overdistend or fatigue the myometrium.<br><br>Cervical laceration (A) causes PPH with a firm uterus; retained placenta (B) causes PPH when the placenta fails to deliver; coagulation defect (D) contributes but is rarely the primary cause of immediate PPH.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q122
  {q:'Postpartum hemorrhage is defined as blood loss of more than how much following vaginal delivery?',
  o:['250 mL','500 mL','1000 mL','300 mL'],a:1,
  e:`Postpartum haemorrhage is defined as blood loss of 500 ml or more following vaginal delivery: this threshold is the standard clinical definition.<br><br>PPH affected 13% of all pregnancies in England in 2011 and 2012, with 17 direct deaths due to obstetric haemorrhage between 2009 and 2012 in the UK and Ireland.<br><br>250 mL (A) and 300 mL (D) are below the accepted threshold; 1,000 mL (C) is the threshold for major PPH after vaginal delivery in some definitions, but the standard definition is 500 mL.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q123
  {q:'The most common cause of primary postpartum hemorrhage is:',
  o:['Retained placenta','Cervical laceration','Coagulopathy','Uterine atony'],a:3,
  e:`Uterine atony is the most common cause of primary postpartum haemorrhage, responsible for approximately 70–80% of cases, accounting for approximately 70–80% of primary PPH cases.<br><br>The uterus fails to contract sufficiently after placental delivery, leaving the large placental bed vessels open and bleeding uncontrolled : the four T's of PPH are Tone (atony, commonest), Trauma (lacerations), Tissue (retained products) and Thrombin (coagulopathy).<br><br>Retained placenta (A) and coagulopathy (C) are less common primary causes; cervical laceration (B) is a Trauma cause that presents with a firm uterus but ongoing haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q124 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'A woman develops heavy bleeding 10 days after delivery. What type of postpartum hemorrhage is this?',
  o:['Primary postpartum hemorrhage','Secondary postpartum hemorrhage','Concealed hemorrhage','Placental site hemorrhage'],a:1,
  e:`Secondary postpartum haemorrhage (PPH) is defined as fresh bleeding from the genital tract between 24 hours and 12 weeks after delivery.<br><br>Bleeding occurring 10 days postpartum falls clearly within this definition and is most commonly caused by retained placental tissue, endometritis or subinvolution of the placental site : often a combination of retained products providing a culture medium for infection.<br><br>Primary PPH (A) occurs within 24 hours of delivery; concealed haemorrhage (C) implies no external bleeding; placental site haemorrhage (D) is a contributing cause of secondary PPH but is not the classification term.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q125 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'Which uterotonic drug is considered the first-line treatment for postpartum hemorrhage due to uterine atony?',
  o:['Ergometrine','Misoprostol','Carboprost','Oxytocin'],a:3,
  e:`Oxytocin is the first-line uterotonic for both prevention and treatment of PPH due to uterine atony, administered immediately after placental delivery as standard active management.<br><br>Administered as an intravenous infusion (syntocinon) after delivery of the placenta as the cornerstone of active management of the third stage: prophylactic use of oxytocin for high-risk patients is specifically recommended to prevent uterine atony.<br><br>Ergometrine (A) is combined with oxytocin as Syntometrine but is contraindicated in hypertension; misoprostol (B) is the sublingual/rectal alternative when oxytocin is unavailable; carboprost (C) is a prostaglandin F2-alpha analogue used as second-line treatment.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q126 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'A patient develops antepartum hemorrhage at 34 weeks with painless vaginal bleeding. The most likely cause is:',
  o:['Vasa previa','Placenta previa','Placental abruption','Cervical ectropion'],a:1,
  e:`The characteristic presenting complaint of placenta previa is painless vaginal bleeding: a placenta covering or encroaching on the cervical os bleeds when the lower uterine segment forms in the third trimester.<br><br>Separating trophoblast from the os produces bleeding without uterine contraction or pain, distinguishing it from placental abruption which presents with painful bleeding and a tense rigid abdomen. placenta previa is diagnosed using ultrasound, preferably transvaginal, to measure the placental edge distance from the internal os.<br><br>Vasa previa (A) presents with bleeding at membrane rupture specifically; placental abruption (C) presents with painful bleeding and uterine tenderness; cervical ectropion (D) causes contact bleeding but not the volume of antepartum haemorrhage described.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q127 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A pregnant woman presents with abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, and a tender uterus. The most likely diagnosis is:',
  o:['Placenta previa','Uterine rupture','Vasa previa','Placental abruption'],a:3,
  e:`The characteristic presentation of placental abruption is painful bleeding associated with a tense, rigid abdomen: premature separation of the placenta from the uterine wall produces retroplacental haemorrhage that causes uterine irritability and the classic woody-hard uterus on palpation.<br><br>Directly contrasting with the painless bleeding of placenta previa and the soft uterus that characterises that diagnosis. placenta previa is most dangerous for the mother while placental abruption is more dangerous for the fetus : a key clinical distinction.<br><br>Placenta previa (A) presents with painless bleeding and a soft uterus; uterine rupture (B) typically presents with sudden severe pain and fetal distress in labour; vasa previa (C) presents with bleeding at amniotomy without uterine pain.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q128 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'In placental abruption, bleeding occurs due to:',
  o:['Premature separation of placenta from uterine wall','Rupture of fetal vessels','Placental invasion of myometrium','Erosion of cervical vessels'],a:0,
  e:`Placental abruption is premature separation of the placenta from the uterine wall; bleeding is maternal, from the decidua basalis Bleeding may be revealed or concealed, making visible loss an unreliable measure.<br><br>Bleeding may be revealed or concealed, making visible vaginal bleeding an unreliable indicator of actual blood loss. The degree of vaginal bleeding does not necessarily correlate with the degree of abruption, as abruptions may be concealed.<br><br>Rupture of fetal vessels (B) causes vasa previa haemorrhage, not abruption; placental invasion (C) describes placenta accreta; cervical vessel erosion (D) causes contact bleeding from cervical pathology.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q129 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'The most serious complication of placental abruption is:',
  o:['Preterm birth','Postpartum anaemia','Disseminated intravascular coagulation','Uterine rupture'],a:2,
  e:`Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) is the most serious complication of severe placental abruption, arising from massive thromboplastin release and triggering life-threatening consumptive coagulopathy.<br><br>Massive thromboplastin release from the retroplacental clot triggers widespread coagulation activation, consuming fibrinogen, platelets and clotting factors, producing a coagulopathy that makes haemostasis impossible. Management requires immediate delivery, aggressive blood product replacement and expert multidisciplinary care. complications such as DIC have been reported in severe placental abruption, and cross-matching 6 units of blood is standard practice when abruption is suspected.<br><br>Preterm birth (A) and anaemia (B) are significant but not life-threatening complications; uterine rupture (D) is a separate complication of previous uterine scar, not abruption.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q130 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'Vasa previa is characterized by:',
  o:['Placenta covering the internal os','Fetal vessels crossing internal cervical os','Premature separation of placenta','Placenta accreta spectrum'],a:1,
  e:`Vasa previa occurs when fetal vessels traverse the fetal membranes over the internal cervical os, either from a velamentous cord insertion or an accessory placental lobe.<br><br>Vasa praevia is not dangerous for the mother but is nearly always fatal for the baby if unrecognised; emergency caesarean section is required immediately if the baby is still alive when the diagnosis is suspected.<br><br>Placenta covering the os (A) defines placenta previa; premature separation (C) defines placental abruption; placenta accreta spectrum (D) describes abnormal placental adherence.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q131
  {q:'A patient with placenta previa develops heavy bleeding during labor. What is the definitive management?',
  o:['Bed rest and observation','Blood transfusion alone','Tocolysis','Cesarean section'],a:3,
  e:`Caesarean section is the definitive management for placenta previa with major haemorrhage: a placenta covering or encroaching on the cervical os cannot be delivered vaginally.<br><br>If there is major fetal or maternal compromise, decisions may have to be made about immediate delivery irrespective of gestation; when there is substantial vaginal bleeding (in excess of 500 ml), antenatal corticosteroids should be considered if gestation is under 35 weeks.<br><br>Bed rest (A) and blood transfusion (B) are supportive measures only; tocolysis (C) is contraindicated with active haemorrhage from placenta previa.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q132 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'A patient develops severe bleeding after delivery due to retained placental fragments. What is the management?',
  o:['Surgical evacuation of uterus','Observation only','Tocolysis','Cervical cerclage'],a:0,
  e:`Surgical evacuation of the uterus, manual removal of the placenta or suction evacuation, is the definitive management for retained placental fragments causing postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>Secondary PPH is defined as fresh bleeding from the genital tract between 24 hours and 12 weeks after delivery; surgical evacuation of the uterus is a recognised treatment in this context.<br><br>Observation only (B) is inappropriate for haemorrhage; tocolysis (C) would worsen haemorrhage by relaxing the uterus; cervical cerclage (D) has no role in postpartum management.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q133 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'The four major causes of postpartum hemorrhage are commonly remembered as:',
  o:['Placenta, perfusion, pressure, position','Atony, accreta, anatomy, abscess','Uterus, vessels, cervix, vagina','Tone, trauma, tissue, thrombin'],a:3,
  e:`The four T's, Tone, Trauma, Tissue and Thrombin, is the universally used mnemonic for the major causes of postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>Uterine causes of haemorrhage include atony (commonest cause), uterine inversion and rupture; there are three main areas from which haemorrhage occurs : uterus, placenta and cervix/vagina.<br><br>The other options (A, B, C) are not recognised clinical mnemonics for PPH causes and would not guide clinical assessment or management.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q134 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'A woman with postpartum hemorrhage has a firm uterus but continued vaginal bleeding. What is the most likely cause?',
  o:['Uterine atony','Cervical or vaginal laceration','Retained placenta','DIC'],a:1,
  e:`Continued vaginal bleeding with a well-contracted firm uterus after delivery points to genital tract trauma, specifically cervical or vaginal laceration, as the source of haemorrhage.<br><br>There are three main areas from which haemorrhage occurs: uterus, placenta and cervix/vagina : when the uterus is firm and the placenta is complete, vaginal or cervical laceration must be systematically sought.<br><br>Uterine atony (A) produces a soft boggy uterus; retained placenta (C) causes the uterus not to contract firmly; DIC (D) can occur but is a systemic complication rather than the anatomical cause.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q135 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'Placenta accreta occurs when:',
  o:['Placenta covers the cervical os','Placenta invades myometrium deeply','Placenta invades deeply into myometrium','Placenta attaches superficially without decidua'],a:3,
  e:`Placenta accreta occurs when the placenta attaches directly to the myometrium without an intervening decidua basalis, most commonly at the site of a previous uterine scar.<br><br>The risk of placenta accreta is greater than 60% for women who have had three or more previous caesarean sections : making it a major obstetric complication of the rising global caesarean section rate.<br><br>Placenta covering the os (A) is placenta previa; deep myometrial invasion (B) is placenta increta; invading bladder wall (C) is percreta : both are more severe forms of the accreta spectrum.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q136
  {q:'Placenta increta refers to:',
  o:['Placenta covering the os','Placenta invading myometrium','Placenta invading through serosa','Placenta accreta with haemorrhage'],a:1,
  e:`Placenta increta is the intermediate form of abnormal placental adherence in which chorionic villi invade deeply into, but do not penetrate through, the myometrium.<br><br>All forms of placenta accreta spectrum are associated with previous uterine surgery, and the risk increases progressively with the number of prior caesarean sections : exceeding 60% after three or more caesareans when concurrent placenta previa is present.<br><br>Placenta covering the os (A) is placenta previa; penetration through serosa (C) is percreta; accreta with haemorrhage (D) is not a recognised classification term.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q137 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'Placenta percreta is characterized by:',
  o:['Superficial villous attachment without decidua','Normal villous attachment','Placenta invading bladder wall','Placenta invading through serosa into adjacent organs'],a:3,
  e:`Placenta percreta is the most severe form of the accreta spectrum, characterised by chorionic villi penetrating completely through the uterine serosa.<br><br>The risk of accreta spectrum disorders increases with the number of previous caesarean sections : exceeding 60% after three caesareans in the presence of placenta previa.<br><br>Superficial attachment without decidua (A) is placenta accreta; normal attachment (B) is completely normal; bladder wall invasion specifically (C) is one manifestation of percreta but not the complete definition.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q138
  {q:'The most important risk factor for placenta accreta is:',
  o:['Grand multiparity','Previous PPH','Previous cesarean section','Uterine fibroids'],a:2,
  e:`Previous caesarean section is the most important risk factor for placenta accreta spectrum: the decidua is deficient or absent at the uterine scar site, allowing chorionic villi to invade directly into the myometrium.<br><br>The risk increases progressively with each additional caesarean section, exceeding 60% for women with three or more prior caesarean sections when concurrent placenta previa is present. the rising global caesarean section rate is directly driving an increase in placenta accreta spectrum disorders.<br><br>Grand multiparity (A) carries some increased risk; previous PPH (B) does not specifically predispose to accreta; uterine fibroids (D) may distort placentation but are not the primary risk factor for accreta.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q139 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'The most common cause of secondary postpartum hemorrhage is:',
  o:['Uterine atony','Cervical laceration','Coagulopathy','Retained placental tissue'],a:3,
  e:`Retained placental tissue is the most common cause of secondary postpartum haemorrhage (PPH), defined as fresh bleeding from the genital tract between 24 hours and 12 weeks after delivery.<br><br>Fragments of placenta or membranes remaining in the uterus prevent adequate myometrial contraction, maintain an open vascular placental bed and serve as a focus for endometritis : the combination of bleeding and infection is the classic presentation of secondary PPH from retained products.<br><br>Uterine atony (A) is the most common cause of primary PPH; cervical laceration (B) causes primary PPH; coagulopathy (C) complicates secondary PPH but is rarely the primary cause.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q140 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'A woman develops postpartum hemorrhage due to uterine atony. Which immediate bedside measure is first-line?',
  o:['B-Lynch suture','Uterine massage','Blood transfusion','Hysterectomy'],a:1,
  e:`Uterine massage, bimanual compression of the uterus, is the immediate bedside first-line measure for PPH due to uterine atony, applied simultaneously with intravenous oxytocin infusion.<br><br>Failure of uterus to contract following delivery of the placenta is the key warning sign of atonic PPH, and immediate massage plus oxytocin should be initiated without delay.<br><br>B-Lynch suture (A) is a surgical intervention escalated after medical management fails; blood transfusion (C) is a resuscitative measure not a uterine treatment; hysterectomy (D) is the last resort after all other measures have failed.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q141 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A patient continues bleeding despite uterotonics and uterine massage. What is the next surgical step?',
  o:['Hysterectomy immediately','Blood transfusion alone','Cervical suturing','B-Lynch uterine compression suture'],a:3,
  e:`The B-Lynch uterine compression suture is a surgical technique applied when uterotonic drugs and uterine massage have failed to control PPH from atony.<br><br>Early recourse to hysterectomy should be considered if simpler medical and surgical interventions prove ineffective; the algorithm of escalation proceeds from medical to surgical to hysterectomy.<br><br>Immediate hysterectomy (A) is premature before B-Lynch and other conservative surgical options are tried; blood transfusion alone (B) does not address the surgical source; cervical suturing (C) is for cervical lacerations, not atonic PPH.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q142 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'A pregnant woman presents with painless vaginal bleeding and ultrasound shows the placenta covering the internal os. What is the diagnosis?',
  o:['Placenta previa','Placental abruption','Vasa previa','Placenta accreta'],a:0,
  e:`Placenta previa is a placenta covering or encroaching on the internal cervical os, presenting characteristically with painless vaginal bleeding confirmed by transvaginal ultrasound.<br><br>Diagnosis is confirmed by transvaginal ultrasound measuring the placental edge from the internal os; complete coverage requires planned caesarean delivery. Placenta praevia is most dangerous for the mother; placental abruption is more dangerous for the fetus than the mother.<br><br>Placental abruption (B) presents with painful bleeding and tense uterus; vasa previa (C) presents with bleeding at membrane rupture; placenta accreta (D) is abnormal adherence, not a covering of the os.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q143
  {q:'In placental abruption, fetal distress occurs mainly due to:',
  o:['Fetal anaemia','Maternal hypovolaemia','Direct fetal injury','Reduced placental perfusion'],a:3,
  e:`Fetal distress in placental abruption results primarily from acute reduction in placental perfusion: premature separation of the placenta reduces the functional area available for oxygen exchange, and the retroplacental haematoma compresses and distorts the remaining placental tissue.<br><br>Placental abruption is acutely dangerous for both the mother and fetus; the absence of a tense abdomen does not rule it out and patients should be managed on their clinical findings.<br><br>Fetal anaemia (A) may occur with fetomaternal haemorrhage but is secondary; maternal hypovolaemia (B) compounds fetal compromise but the primary mechanism is placental rather than maternal circulation; direct fetal injury (C) is rare in abruption.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q144 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'The most common clinical sign of uterine rupture during labor is:',
  o:['Painless vaginal bleeding','Tachycardia alone','Sudden severe abdominal pain with fetal distress','Hypertension'],a:2,
  e:`Sudden severe abdominal pain accompanied by fetal distress, typically manifesting as fetal bradycardia or late decelerations on CTG, is the most common clinical presentation of uterine rupture during labour.<br><br>The pain results from peritoneal irritation by intraperitoneal haemorrhage or organ extrusion, and the simultaneous fetal compromise reflects disruption of uteroplacental circulation when the uterine wall breaches. uterine rupture is a life-threatening obstetric emergency requiring immediate caesarean section and surgical repair or hysterectomy.<br><br>Painless vaginal bleeding (A) is the hallmark of placenta previa; tachycardia alone (B) is non-specific; hypertension (D) occurs in pre-eclampsia and is not characteristic of uterine rupture.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q145 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'A woman with severe postpartum hemorrhage develops hypotension and tachycardia. What complication is this?',
  o:['Hypovolemic shock','Septic shock','Neurogenic shock','Anaphylactic shock'],a:0,
  e:`Hypovolaemic shock from massive obstetric haemorrhage presents with hypotension and tachycardia, the classic haemodynamic signs of intravascular volume depletion, the classic haemodynamic signs of intravascular volume depletion.<br><br>Hypotension is a very late sign in blood loss, occurring after approximately 2,000 ml of loss as young fit women compensate extremely well, tachycardia, rising fundus and oliguria precede hypotension and should trigger urgent action without waiting for blood pressure to fall.<br><br>Septic shock (B) has warm, well-perfused peripheries initially; neurogenic shock (C) causes bradycardia; anaphylactic shock (D) is associated with urticaria, bronchospasm and exposure to allergen.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q146 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'The most important initial step in management of obstetric hemorrhage is:',
  o:['Hysterectomy','Oxytocin infusion','Blood transfusion','Stabilization and fluid resuscitation'],a:3,
  e:`Stabilisation and fluid resuscitation, establishing large-bore intravenous access, initiating crystalloid or colloid infusion, sending blood for cross-match and initiating blood product replacement, is the most important immediate step in managing obstetric haemorrhage.<br><br>Do not delay fluid resuscitation and blood transfusion because of false reassurance from a single haemoglobin result : treat the patient, not the result. resuscitation proceeds simultaneously with identification and treatment of the haemorrhage source, with early recourse to blood components before coagulation indices deteriorate.<br><br>Hysterectomy (A) is a last resort; oxytocin infusion (B) addresses atony specifically but resuscitation precedes it; blood transfusion (C) is part of resuscitation but must follow initial volume restoration with IV fluids.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q147 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'Which coagulation disorder may develop in severe placental abruption?',
  o:['Von Willebrand disease','Disseminated intravascular coagulation','Immune thrombocytopenia','Haemophilia A'],a:1,
  e:`Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) is the coagulation disorder that may develop in severe placental abruption: massive release of thromboplastin from the retroplacental clot into the maternal circulation triggers widespread coagulation activation, consuming fibrinogen, platelets and clotting factors.<br><br>Producing a life-threatening consumptive coagulopathy that requires urgent blood product replacement alongside delivery. complications such as DIC have been reported in severe placental abruption; cross-matching 6 units of blood is standard in suspected abruption/praevia.<br><br>Von Willebrand disease (A), immune thrombocytopenia (C) and haemophilia A (D) are all pre-existing inherited conditions : they do not develop as acute complications of placental abruption.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q148 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'A fetus dies suddenly after rupture of membranes due to bleeding from fetal vessels. What is the diagnosis?',
  o:['Placental abruption','Placenta previa','Cord prolapse','Vasa previa'],a:3,
  e:`Vasa previa is the diagnosis when fetal vessels traversing the fetal membranes over the internal os rupture at the time of membrane rupture.<br><br>The bleeding in vasa previa is fetal blood, not maternal : a distinguishing feature, as rupturing the membranes converts painless antepartum bleeding into catastrophic fetal haemorrhage.<br><br>Placental abruption (A) causes maternal bleeding; placenta previa (B) causes maternal bleeding; cord prolapse (C) causes mechanical cord compression, not haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q149 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'The most effective drug for preventing postpartum hemorrhage during active management of third stage of labor is:',
  o:['Oxytocin','Ergometrine','Misoprostol','Carboprost'],a:0,
  e:`Oxytocin is the most effective drug for preventing PPH during active management of the third stage of labour, reducing PPH incidence by approximately 60% versus physiological management.<br><br>Administered as a slow intravenous bolus (5 or 10 units) or intramuscular injection immediately after delivery of the anterior shoulder or after placental delivery: prophylactic use of oxytocin agents for high-risk patients is specifically recommended to prevent uterine atony.<br><br>Ergometrine (B) is effective but contraindicated in hypertension and has more side effects; misoprostol (C) is used where oxytocin is unavailable (sublingual or rectal); carboprost (D) is reserved for treatment of established atonic PPH.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q150
  {q:'A woman develops massive bleeding after delivery due to failure of placenta to separate. What is the most likely diagnosis?',
  o:['Uterine atony','Placenta accreta spectrum','Retained placenta only','DIC'],a:1,
  e:`Placenta accreta spectrum (PAS), encompassing accreta, increta and percreta, presents with massive haemorrhage at delivery when the abnormally adherent placenta fails to separate from the uterine wall.<br><br>The risk of placenta accreta spectrum is greater than 60% for women who have had three or more previous caesarean sections when placenta previa is also present.<br><br>Uterine atony (A) causes haemorrhage after placental delivery, not failure to separate; retained placenta alone (C) implies manual removal is possible; DIC (D) complicates accreta but is not the primary diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q151
  {q:'Multiple pregnancy is defined as pregnancy with:',
  o:['More than one fetus in the uterus','Fetus weighing more than 4 kg','Pregnancy lasting more than 40 weeks','Fetus with more than one placenta'],a:0,
  e:`Multiple pregnancy is simply defined as the presence of more than one fetus in the uterus simultaneously, with twins accounting for the vast majority of multiple gestations.<br><br>Twins account for the vast majority of multiple pregnancies, with triplets and higher-order multiples less common : the incidence of multiple pregnancy has increased significantly with the rise of assisted reproductive technologies including ovulation induction and IVF.<br><br>Fetus weighing more than 4 kg (B) describes macrosomia; pregnancy lasting more than 40 weeks (C) describes prolonged pregnancy; more than one placenta (D) describes the placentation of dizygotic twins but is not the definition of multiple pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q152 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'The most common type of twin pregnancy is:',
  o:['Monozygotic twins','Monochorionic diamniotic twins','Monochorionic monoamniotic twins','Dizygotic twins'],a:3,
  e:`Dizygotic (fraternal) twins, arising from fertilization of two separate ova by two separate spermatozoa, are the most common type of twin pregnancy, accounting for approximately two-thirds of all twins.<br><br>They are always dichorionic diamniotic (each twin has its own placenta and amniotic sac) and may be of different sexes, reflecting their separate genetic origins.<br><br>Monozygotic twins (A) arise from a single fertilised ovum; monochorionic diamniotic (B) and monoamniotic (C) types are subsets of monozygotic twins : all are less common than dizygotic.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q153 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'Dizygotic twins occur due to:',
  o:['Division of a single fertilized ovum','Incomplete division of the embryo','Fertilization of two separate ova by two sperms','Error in meiosis producing two eggs'],a:2,
  e:`Dizygotic twins result from the fertilization of two separate ova by two separate spermatozoa : effectively two simultaneous pregnancies occurring at the same time.<br><br>The double ovulation necessary for dizygotic twinning may occur spontaneously (more common with advanced maternal age) or be induced by fertility treatments including clomiphene citrate and gonadotropin stimulation.<br><br>Division of a single ovum (A, B) describes monozygotic twinning; errors in meiosis (D) produce aneuploidy rather than dizygotic twinning.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q154
  {q:'Monozygotic twins arise from:',
  o:['Fertilization of two ova','Division of a single fertilized ovum','Chromosomal duplication','Androgenetic genome'],a:1,
  e:`Monozygotic (identical) twins arise from division of a single fertilised ovum at various points after fertilization, with the timing of division determining chorionicity and amnionicity.<br><br>The specific mechanism that triggers monozygotic splitting is not fully understood; unlike dizygotic twinning, monozygotic twinning rates are relatively constant worldwide and are not significantly influenced by age or fertility treatment.<br><br>Fertilization of two ova (A) produces dizygotic twins; chromosomal duplication (C) is not the mechanism; androgenetic genome (D) is the feature of complete molar pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q155
  {q:'If division of the zygote occurs within the first 3 days after fertilization, the resulting twins will be:',
  o:['Dichorionic diamniotic','Monochorionic diamniotic','Monochorionic monoamniotic','Conjoined twins'],a:0,
  e:`Division of the zygote within the first 3 days after fertilization, while the morula is still in the fallopian tube before implantation, produces dichorionic diamniotic twins.<br><br>Each twin develops its own separate chorion and amnion, functionally equivalent to dizygotic twins in terms of placentation and carrying the lowest risk of the monozygotic twin complications.<br><br>Monochorionic diamniotic (B) results from days 4–8; monochorionic monoamniotic (C) from days 8–13; conjoined twins (D) from division after day 13.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q156 : rotated: correct = D
  {q:'Division of the embryo between days 4-8 after fertilization results in:',
  o:['Dichorionic diamniotic twins','Conjoined twins','Monochorionic monoamniotic twins','Monochorionic diamniotic twins'],a:3,
  e:`Division of the embryo between days 4 and 8, after the inner cell mass has formed but before the amnion develops, results in monochorionic diamniotic twins.<br><br>Both twins share a single chorion (and therefore a single placenta) but each develops within its own amnion, producing the most common type of monozygotic twinning and placing the pregnancy at risk of twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome.<br><br>Dichorionic diamniotic (A) results from division within day 3; conjoined twins (B) from after day 13; monochorionic monoamniotic (C) from days 8–13.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q157 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'Division of the embryo between days 8-13 after fertilization produces:',
  o:['Dichorionic diamniotic twins','Monochorionic monoamniotic twins','Conjoined twins','Monochorionic diamniotic twins'],a:1,
  e:`Division between days 8 and 13, after the amnion has formed but before gastrulation, produces monochorionic monoamniotic twins, the rarest and highest-risk form of monozygotic twinning.<br><br>Cord entanglement is the most dangerous complication of monoamniotic twins, occurring in virtually all monoamniotic twin pregnancies and carrying a high risk of sudden fetal death.<br><br>Dichorionic diamniotic (A) is from day 1–3; conjoined twins (C) result from incomplete division after day 13; monochorionic diamniotic (D) is from days 4–8.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q158 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'Division occurring after day 13 following fertilization may result in:',
  o:['Dichorionic diamniotic twins','Monochorionic monoamniotic twins','Conjoined twins','Triplets'],a:2,
  e:`Division of the embryo after day 13, when gastrulation and primitive streak formation have already begun, produces conjoined twins because complete separation is no longer possible.<br><br>The partially divided embryo remains fused at the site where separation is incomplete, and the degree of fusion determines the anatomical type (thoracopagus, omphalopagus, craniopagus, etc.).<br><br>Dichorionic diamniotic (A) results from division within day 3; monochorionic monoamniotic (B) from days 8–13; triplets (D) require three ova or two division events.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q159
  {q:'The most reliable ultrasound sign in early pregnancy to diagnose dichorionic twin pregnancy is:',
  o:['Lambda sign','T sign','Polyhydramnios','Fused placentas'],a:0,
  e:`The lambda (twin peak) sign is the most reliable ultrasound marker for identifying dichorionic twin pregnancy in the first trimester.<br><br>It appears as a triangular wedge of placental tissue projecting into the base of the inter-twin membrane between the two chorionic layers, produced by villous tissue growing into the inter-twin membrane : it is most reliably seen before 14 weeks and becomes less reliable as pregnancy advances.<br><br>The T sign (B) indicates monochorionic twins with a thin inter-twin membrane; polyhydramnios (C) is a later finding; fused placentas (D) may occur in dichorionic twins but is not a reliable early diagnostic sign.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q160 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'The ultrasound sign suggesting monochorionic twins is:',
  o:['Lambda sign','Discordant growth','T sign','Polyhydramnios'],a:2,
  e:`The T sign is the ultrasound marker of monochorionic twin pregnancy: the inter-twin membrane meets the placenta at a right angle (forming a T), reflecting the absence of chorionic villi invading the membrane base.<br><br>Accurate identification of the T sign before 14 weeks allows correct chorionicity assignment, which is the most important piece of early pregnancy information in twin pregnancies, dictating surveillance frequency and management protocols.<br><br>Lambda sign (A) indicates dichorionic twins; discordant growth (B) and polyhydramnios (D) are later complications of twin pregnancy rather than early chorionicity markers.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q161 : rotated: correct = C
  {q:'The most common complication of monochorionic twin pregnancy is:',
  o:['Conjoined twins','Twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome','Cord entanglement','Vanishing twin syndrome'],a:1,
  e:`Twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome (TTTS) is unique to monochorionic pregnancy and is the most common serious complication, affecting approximately 10–15% of monochorionic diamniotic pregnancies.<br><br>Approximately 10–15% of monochorionic diamniotic pregnancies develop TTTS due to unbalanced vascular anastomoses in the shared placenta, resulting in the classic oligohydramnios-polyhydramnios sequence with the donor twin becoming anaemic and the recipient developing fluid overload and cardiac compromise.<br><br>Conjoined twins (A) are a complication of monoamniotic, not monochorionic diamniotic pregnancy; cord entanglement (C) is specific to monoamniotic twins; vanishing twin syndrome (D) is an early first-trimester phenomenon.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q162 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'Twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome occurs due to:',
  o:['Chromosomal abnormality','Placental previa','Discordant fetal growth only','Vascular anastomoses between twins'],a:3,
  e:`TTTS occurs due to unbalanced vascular anastomoses in the shared monochorionic placenta: four types of vascular connections exist in monochorionic pregnancies.<br><br>Arteriovenous (AV), venoarterial (VA), arterioarterial (AA) and venovenous (VV); when AV connections are unbalanced (more flow in one direction than the other), alterations in hydrostatic and osmotic forces produce the TTTS sequence, while AA anastomoses are actually protective against TTTS development.<br><br>Chromosomal abnormality (A) causes structural fetal anomalies; placenta previa (B) causes antepartum haemorrhage; discordant growth alone (C) does not define TTTS.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q163
  {q:'In twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome, the donor twin typically develops:',
  o:['Polyhydramnios','Hydrops fetalis','Oligohydramnios','Macrosomia'],a:2,
  e:`In TTTS, the donor twin loses blood volume through the unbalanced arteriovenous placental anastomoses and typically develops oligohydramnios, reduced amniotic fluid, due to decreased fetal urine output from reduced renal perfusion and relative hypovolaemia.<br><br>TTTS is diagnosed by the combination of oligohydramnios (MVP less than 2 cm) in the donor sac and polyhydramnios (MVP greater than 8 cm) in the recipient sac.<br><br>Polyhydramnios (A) is the finding in the recipient twin; hydrops (B) may develop in the recipient twin from cardiac failure; macrosomia (D) is not a feature of the donor twin.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q164 : rotated: correct = B
  {q:'In twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome, the recipient twin usually develops:',
  o:['Oligohydramnios','Polyhydramnios','Anaemia','Intrauterine growth restriction'],a:1,
  e:`The recipient twin in TTTS receives excess blood volume through the unbalanced placental anastomoses and develops polyhydramnios, excessive amniotic fluid, from increased fetal urine production driven by hypervolaemia and high renal perfusion.<br><br>TTTS is diagnosed when oligohydramnios (MVP less than 2 cm) is present in one sac and polyhydramnios (MVP greater than 8 cm) in the other : the combination of both findings is required.<br><br>Oligohydramnios (A) is the finding in the donor twin; anaemia (C) and IUGR (D) are features of the donor, not the recipient.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q165 : rotated: correct = A
  {q:'The most common presentation of the first twin at delivery is:',
  o:['Cephalic','Breech','Transverse','Oblique'],a:0,
  e:`Cephalic (vertex) presentation is the most common presentation of the first twin at the time of delivery, occurring in approximately 45–50% of twin deliveries.<br><br>When the first twin is cephalic, vaginal delivery is the standard recommendation regardless of the presentation of the second twin, as the successful delivery of the first twin creates space for internal podalic version or assisted breech delivery of the second twin if needed.<br><br>Breech (B) is the most common presentation for the second twin; transverse (C) and oblique (D) are unstable lies that require active management during labour.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q166
  {q:'The most common maternal complication of multiple pregnancy is:',
  o:['Pre-eclampsia','Gestational diabetes','Anaemia','Postpartum hemorrhage'],a:3,
  e:`Postpartum haemorrhage is the most common maternal complication of multiple pregnancy, driven by uterine overdistension from two or more fetuses causing myometrial fatigue and atony.<br><br>Uterine overdistension from two or more fetuses fatigues the myometrium, predisposing to atony after delivery, the commonest cause of PPH. Pre-eclampsia and anaemia are also significantly increased in multiple pregnancy, but PPH from atony has the highest incidence among maternal complications.<br><br>Pre-eclampsia (A) is increased but less universal than PPH; gestational diabetes (B) is modestly increased; anaemia (C) occurs in twin pregnancy mainly due to increased plasma volume and fetal demand.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q167
  {q:'The most common fetal complication in twin pregnancy is:',
  o:['Congenital anomalies','Preterm birth','Twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome','Cord entanglement'],a:1,
  e:`Preterm birth is the most common and clinically important fetal complication of twin pregnancy: approximately 60% of twin pregnancies result in spontaneous birth before 37 weeks' gestation, and multiple gestations account for 20–25% of NICU admissions.<br><br>The most common cause of perinatal mortality in twins is prematurity and its associated complications. the overall perinatal mortality for monochorionic twins is estimated at 30 per 1,000, compared with 3.8 per 1,000 among dichorionic twins.<br><br>Congenital anomalies (A) are increased in monozygotic twins but are less common than preterm birth as a cause of morbidity; TTTS (C) affects approximately 10–15% of monochorionic twins specifically; cord entanglement (D) is limited to monoamniotic twins.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q168 : rotated: correct=D (prev Q167=B)
  {q:'A condition in which one twin dies and becomes flattened and compressed in utero is called:',
  o:['Vanishing twin syndrome','Twin anemia polycythemia sequence','Hydrops fetalis','Fetus papyraceus'],a:3,
  e:`Fetus papyraceus (papyraceous fetus) describes the condition where one twin dies in the second trimester and becomes mummified, compressed and flattened between the membranes and the uterine wall as the surviving co-twin continues to grow.<br><br>The dead twin is dehydrated and paper-thin at delivery, resembling parchment, and is an incidental finding in the placenta after delivery of the surviving twin. this condition most commonly occurs in dichorionic twins and carries a good prognosis for the surviving twin in most cases.<br><br>Vanishing twin syndrome (A) occurs in the first trimester with complete resorption; twin anaemia-polycythaemia sequence (B) is a chronic form of TTTS; hydrops fetalis (C) is oedema of the living fetus.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q169 : rotated: correct=C (prev Q168=D)
  {q:'The disappearance of one twin in early pregnancy is known as:',
  o:['Twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome','Fetus papyraceus','Vanishing twin syndrome','Conjoined twins'],a:2,
  e:`Vanishing twin syndrome refers to the early intrauterine death and complete resorption of one twin, identified on first-trimester ultrasound, leaving no macroscopic evidence at delivery.<br><br>In the first trimester, intrauterine death of one twin is generally associated with a good outcome for the co-twin, as resorption occurs without significant haemodynamic consequence.<br><br>TTTS (A) is a later second-trimester complication; fetus papyraceus (B) is the mummified remnant of a later death; conjoined twins (D) arise from incomplete embryonic division.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q170
  {q:'The most accurate method for determining chorionicity in twin pregnancy is:',
  o:['Ultrasound in first trimester','Second trimester ultrasound','Third trimester ultrasound','Doppler study'],a:0,
  e:`First-trimester ultrasound, ideally performed before 14 weeks, is the most accurate method for determining chorionicity and amnionicity in twin pregnancies.<br><br>The lambda sign (twin peak sign) reliably identifies dichorionic twins while the T sign identifies monochorionic twins, both being most reliably visualised before 14 weeks after which the membrane base becomes less distinct.<br><br>Second trimester (B) and third trimester (C) ultrasound are less accurate for chorionicity; Doppler (D) assesses fetal wellbeing but does not determine chorionicity.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q171
  {q:'The most common congenital anomaly in monozygotic twins is:',
  o:['Neural tube defect','Congenital heart disease','Anencephaly','Omphalocele'],a:1,
  e:`Congenital heart disease is the most common structural anomaly in monozygotic twins, predisposing to cardiac defects through disrupted embryonic lateralisation.<br><br>Monozygotic twinning disrupts normal lateralisation signals and cardiac looping during early embryogenesis, predisposing to structural cardiac defects. The risk of congenital anomalies overall is substantially higher in monochorionic twins than in dizygotic twins, reflecting the shared genetic and developmental environment of monozygotic twinning.<br><br>Neural tube defects (A), anencephaly (C) and omphalocele (D) are recognised but less common structural anomalies in twins than congenital heart disease.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q172
  {q:'Which maternal factor increases the likelihood of dizygotic twins?',
  o:['Young maternal age','Nulliparity','Advanced maternal age','Short maternal stature'],a:2,
  e:`Advanced maternal age increases the likelihood of dizygotic twinning because rising FSH levels in older women stimulate the development of multiple follicles, increasing the chance of double ovulation in a single cycle.<br><br>This explains the well-established association between maternal age and dizygotic twin rates : women aged 35–40 have a significantly higher rate of spontaneous dizygotic twinning than women in their twenties.<br><br>Young maternal age (A) is associated with lower, not higher, dizygotic twin rates; nulliparity (B) is not a risk factor; short stature (D) has no established effect on twinning rates.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q173
  {q:'Which drug used in infertility treatment increases the risk of multiple pregnancy?',
  o:['Oxytocin','Clomiphene citrate','Methotrexate','Progesterone'],a:1,
  e:`Clomiphene citrate, an anti-oestrogen used to induce ovulation, increases the risk of multiple pregnancy by stimulating the development of multiple follicles simultaneously, leading to double or multiple ovulation.<br><br>Gonadotropin stimulation used in assisted reproduction carries an even higher risk of multiple pregnancy, which is why single embryo transfer policies have been adopted in IVF programmes to minimise this complication.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) stimulates uterine contractions and does not induce ovulation; methotrexate (C) treats ectopic pregnancy and is not used for ovulation induction; progesterone (D) supports the luteal phase but does not stimulate multiple follicle development.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q174
  {q:'In twin pregnancy, fundal height is usually:',
  o:['Smaller than gestational age','Equal to gestational age','Larger than gestational age','Absent'],a:2,
  e:`In twin pregnancy, the uterus contains two fetuses, two placentas and increased amniotic fluid volume, producing a fundal height consistently larger than expected for dates.<br><br>Producing a fundal height that is consistently larger than expected for gestational age: the fundal height may be 4–6 cm greater than the gestational age in weeks, which is one of the clinical indicators that raises suspicion for multiple pregnancy before ultrasound confirmation.<br><br>Smaller (A) or equal (B) fundal height would occur in growth-restricted twin pregnancies or measurements at earlier gestations; absent fundal height (D) is not a physiological finding in twin pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q175 : rotated: correct=D (prev Q174=C)
  {q:'The most common placental arrangement in twin pregnancy is:',
  o:['Monochorionic monoamniotic','Monochorionic diamniotic','Conjoined twins','Dichorionic diamniotic'],a:3,
  e:`Dichorionic diamniotic placentation is the most common placental arrangement in twin pregnancy overall: all dizygotic (fraternal) twins are dichorionic diamniotic, and approximately one-third of monozygotic twins are also dichorionic diamniotic (when division occurs within the first 3 days).<br><br>Together making dichorionic diamniotic the most frequent arrangement seen in clinical practice. dichorionic twins carry a substantially lower risk of the serious complications of monochorionic pregnancy including TTTS, twin anaemia-polycythaemia sequence and co-twin death from shared circulation.<br><br>Monochorionic monoamniotic (A) and monochorionic diamniotic (B) are monozygotic subtypes; conjoined twins (C) arise from late division after day 13 and are the rarest type.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q176 : rotated: correct=A (prev Q175=D)
  {q:'The risk of congenital anomalies is highest in:',
  o:['Monochorionic twins','Dizygotic twins','Dichorionic twins','Twins conceived naturally'],a:0,
  e:`Monochorionic twins carry the highest risk of congenital anomalies among all twin types, alongside unique haemodynamic complications of the shared placentation.<br><br>Monozygotic splitting and the shared vascular environment predispose to cardiac defects, neural tube defects and midline anomalies, alongside TTTS and twin reversed arterial perfusion. The overall perinatal mortality for monochorionic twins is estimated at 30 per 1,000, compared with 3.8 per 1,000 among dichorionic twins.<br><br>Dizygotic twins (B) and dichorionic twins (C) have no higher anomaly risk than singletons; natural conception (D) does not independently increase anomaly risk.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q177
  {q:'The most dangerous complication of monoamniotic twins is:',
  o:['Placenta previa','Polyhydramnios','Maternal anemia','Cord entanglement'],a:3,
  e:`Cord entanglement is the most dangerous complication specific to monoamniotic twins : both fetuses share a single amniotic cavity with no dividing membrane separating their umbilical cords, allowing the cords to entwine freely throughout pregnancy.<br><br>Cord entanglement occurs in virtually all monoamniotic twin pregnancies and can lead to acute cord occlusion and sudden fetal death at any point in the third trimester.<br><br>Placenta previa (A) and maternal anaemia (C) are general obstetric complications not specific to monoamniotic twins; polyhydramnios (B) may occur but is not the most dangerous complication.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q178
  {q:'The recommended mode of delivery when first twin is cephalic and second twin breech is:',
  o:['Elective cesarean section','Vaginal delivery','Hysterectomy','Forceps delivery'],a:1,
  e:`Vaginal delivery is the recommended mode of delivery when the first twin presents cephalically regardless of the second twin's presentation.<br><br>This approach is supported by evidence from the Twin Birth Study and current NICE guidelines, which recommend vaginal delivery as the standard when the leading twin is cephalic.<br><br>Elective caesarean (A) is only recommended when the first twin is non-cephalic; hysterectomy (C) has no role in twin delivery mode; forceps (D) may be used for the second twin's head but is not the primary management plan.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q179
  {q:'The most common cause of perinatal mortality in twins is:',
  o:['Congenital anomalies','Birth trauma','Prematurity','Placental abruption'],a:2,
  e:`Prematurity is the most common cause of perinatal mortality in twin pregnancy: approximately 60% of twin pregnancies result in spontaneous birth before 37 weeks, and multiple gestations account for 20–25% of NICU admissions.<br><br>The infant mortality rate for twins is approximately 5.5 times higher than for singletons, mainly as a result of extreme prematurity and its complications including respiratory distress syndrome and intraventricular haemorrhage.<br><br>Congenital anomalies (A) contribute but are less prevalent than prematurity; birth trauma (B) is uncommon with appropriate management; placental abruption (D) is a risk factor but not the leading cause of mortality.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q180 : rotated: correct=C (prev Q179=C)
  {q:'In twin pregnancy, maternal anemia occurs mainly due to:',
  o:['Reduced iron absorption','Increased plasma volume and fetal demand','Decreased hemoglobin synthesis','Reduced erythropoiesis'],a:1,
  e:`Maternal anaemia in twin pregnancy results primarily from the combination of physiologically expanded plasma volume and the increased fetal demand for iron and folate from two fetuses.<br><br>The plasma volume expansion in twin pregnancy is approximately 40–70% above baseline (compared to 40–45% in singleton pregnancies), diluting haemoglobin concentration while simultaneously the two fetuses and placentas draw heavily on maternal iron stores.<br><br>Reduced iron absorption (A) is not specifically increased in twin pregnancy; decreased haemoglobin synthesis (C) and reduced erythropoiesis (D) are not the primary mechanisms : the anaemia is dilutional and demand-related.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q181 : rotated: correct=D (prev Q180=C)
  {q:'Preterm labour is defined as onset of regular uterine contractions with cervical change between:',
  o:['28-40 weeks','20-28 weeks','30-37 weeks','24-36+6 weeks'],a:3,
  e:`Preterm labour is defined as the onset of regular uterine contractions with progressive cervical dilatation and/or effacement occurring between 24 and 36 weeks plus 6 days of gestation.<br><br>This definition specifically excludes the periviable period below 24 weeks (where different management considerations apply) and ends at 36+6 weeks as labour from 37 weeks onwards is classified as term.<br><br>28–40 weeks (A) and 30–37 weeks (C) use incorrect gestational limits; 20–28 weeks (B) includes previable gestations not classified as preterm labour in standard definitions.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q182
  {q:'The most common cause of spontaneous preterm labour is:',
  o:['Placenta previa','Maternal diabetes','Idiopathic','Fetal anomalies'],a:2,
  e:`Idiopathic spontaneous preterm labour, where no identifiable cause is found, is the most common category of preterm labour, accounting for approximately 50% of all cases.<br><br>Known contributing factors include intrauterine infection (bacterial vaginosis, ascending genital tract infection), uterine overdistension (multiple pregnancy, polyhydramnios), placental pathology and previous preterm birth : but none is identified in most spontaneous cases.<br><br>Placenta previa (A) causes antepartum haemorrhage; maternal diabetes (B) is associated with iatrogenic preterm birth; fetal anomalies (D) are a less common cause of spontaneous preterm labour.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q183
  {q:'Which infection is most commonly associated with preterm labour?',
  o:['Upper respiratory infection','Skin infection','Urinary tract infection','Bacterial vaginosis'],a:3,
  e:`Bacterial vaginosis (BV) is the genital tract infection most commonly and strongly associated with spontaneous preterm labour, disrupting lactobacillus-dominant flora and triggering inflammatory cytokine release.<br><br>BV disrupts the normal lactobacillus-dominant vaginal flora, allowing overgrowth of anaerobic organisms that produce proteases and phospholipases capable of triggering inflammatory cytokine release and prostaglandin synthesis : directly stimulating uterine contractions and cervical ripening in a mechanism similar to infection-induced preterm labour.<br><br>Upper respiratory infection (A) and skin infection (B) do not directly trigger uterine contractions; UTI (C) is associated with preterm labour but less specifically than BV.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q184
  {q:'A woman at 32 weeks gestation presents with regular contractions and cervical dilatation of 3 cm. What is the diagnosis?',
  o:['Preterm labour','False labour','Threatened abortion','Term labour'],a:0,
  e:`Preterm labour is diagnosed by the combination of regular uterine contractions and objective cervical change, dilatation and/or effacement, occurring before 37 completed weeks of gestation.<br><br>At 32 weeks with 3 cm cervical dilatation and regular contractions, this is confirmed preterm labour requiring immediate admission, corticosteroids for fetal lung maturity, magnesium sulphate for neuroprotection and consideration of tocolysis to allow time for these agents to work.<br><br>False labour (B) has no cervical change; threatened abortion (C) applies below 24 weeks; term labour (D) begins at 37 weeks or beyond.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q185
  {q:'Which hormone is primarily responsible for maintaining uterine quiescence during pregnancy?',
  o:['Oxytocin','Prostaglandin','Progesterone','Estrogen'],a:2,
  e:`Progesterone is the primary hormone responsible for maintaining uterine quiescence throughout pregnancy: it promotes uterine relaxation by blocking gap junction formation between myometrial cells, reducing oxytocin receptor expression and inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis.<br><br>The withdrawal of progesterone influence, either through absolute decline (as in some animals) or through functional withdrawal mediated by changes in progesterone receptor isoform expression in humans, is a key mechanism initiating the onset of labour at term and preterm.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) stimulates contractions; prostaglandin (B) promotes cervical ripening and contractions; oestrogen (D) rises toward term and counteracts progesterone, contributing to labour onset.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q186
  {q:'Which test is commonly used to predict risk of preterm labour in symptomatic women?',
  o:['Fetal fibronectin test','Biophysical profile','Non-stress test','Amniotic fluid index'],a:0,
  e:`The fetal fibronectin (fFN) test, detecting fibronectin in cervicovaginal secretions between 22 and 34 weeks, is the most clinically useful biochemical predictor of preterm labour in symptomatic women.<br><br>A negative fFN result has a very high negative predictive value (over 95%) for preterm delivery within the next 7–14 days, making it most useful for safely discharging women with symptoms who are at low immediate risk.<br><br>Biophysical profile (B) and non-stress test (C) assess fetal wellbeing; amniotic fluid index (D) detects polyhydramnios or oligohydramnios : none predict preterm labour onset.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q187
  {q:'A cervical length less than what value on transvaginal ultrasound indicates increased risk of preterm labour?',
  o:['30 mm','25 mm','35 mm','15 mm'],a:1,
  e:`A cervical length of less than 25 mm measured by transvaginal ultrasound is the established threshold indicating significantly increased risk of spontaneous preterm labour.<br><br>Transvaginal ultrasound is the most reliable imaging technique for cervical length assessment and is far more accurate than transabdominal measurement in the clinical context of preterm labour risk assessment.<br><br>30 mm (A) and 35 mm (C) are within normal range; 15 mm (D) represents very short cervix but is not the primary threshold : the standard clinical cut-off is 25 mm.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q188
  {q:'Which drug is commonly used as a tocolytic to suppress uterine contractions in preterm labour?',
  o:['Methylergometrine','Misoprostol','Nifedipine','Oxytocin'],a:2,
  e:`Nifedipine, a calcium channel blocker, is one of the most widely used tocolytics for suppressing uterine contractions in preterm labour.<br><br>The most important benefit of tocolysis is to allow time for antenatal corticosteroid administration to accelerate fetal lung maturity : tocolysis does not prevent preterm birth but buys critical time.<br><br>Methylergometrine (A) stimulates uterine contractions; misoprostol (B) is a prostaglandin that ripens the cervix; oxytocin (D) augments labour : all are contraindicated as tocolytics.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q189
  {q:'Which medication is given to accelerate fetal lung maturity in preterm labour?',
  o:['Magnesium sulfate','Betamethasone','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:1,
  e:`Betamethasone is the corticosteroid given to accelerate fetal lung maturity in preterm labour : administered as two intramuscular doses 24 hours apart between 24 and 34 weeks of gestation.<br><br>Antenatal corticosteroids are most beneficial when administered between 24 and 34 weeks, requiring at least 24 hours but ideally 48 hours before delivery to achieve maximum effect.<br><br>Magnesium sulphate (A) is given for neuroprotection against cerebral palsy; progesterone (C) maintains uterine quiescence; oxytocin (D) stimulates labour.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q190
  {q:'Antenatal corticosteroids are most beneficial when administered between:',
  o:['24-34 weeks','20-24 weeks','34-40 weeks','30-38 weeks'],a:0,
  e:`Antenatal corticosteroids are most beneficial between 24 and 34 weeks, and immature enough that respiratory distress syndrome risk remains significant.<br><br>At this window the fetal lung can respond to glucocorticoid stimulation with accelerated surfactant production, yet remains immature enough that RDS risk is clinically significant. A single course of betamethasone (two doses 24 hours apart) is the standard recommendation; repeat courses are not routinely given due to concerns about fetal growth restriction and neurodevelopmental effects.<br><br>Before 24 weeks (B) the lung is too immature to respond meaningfully; after 34 weeks (C, D) the lung is usually sufficiently mature that the risk-benefit ratio of corticosteroids is less favourable.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q191
  {q:'Which medication is administered in preterm labour to reduce risk of cerebral palsy in the neonate?',
  o:['Nifedipine','Betamethasone','Oxytocin','Magnesium sulfate'],a:3,
  e:`Magnesium sulphate is administered in preterm labour before 32–34 weeks specifically to reduce the risk of cerebral palsy and major motor dysfunction in the neonate.<br><br>Evidence from multiple randomised trials demonstrates a significant neuroprotective effect : magnesium stabilises neuronal membranes and reduces excitotoxic injury in the immature brain, with a number-needed-to-treat of approximately 63 to prevent one case of cerebral palsy.<br><br>Nifedipine (A) is a tocolytic; betamethasone (B) promotes lung maturity; oxytocin (C) augments labour : none provide neuroprotection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q192
  {q:'The most common neonatal complication of preterm birth is:',
  o:['Respiratory distress syndrome','Meconium aspiration','Polycythemia','Congenital heart disease'],a:0,
  e:`Respiratory distress syndrome (RDS), caused by surfactant deficiency in the immature preterm lung, is the most common and clinically important neonatal complication of preterm birth.<br><br>Type II pneumocytes do not produce sufficient surfactant before approximately 34–36 weeks, resulting in alveolar collapse, decreased lung compliance and progressive respiratory failure characterised by tachypnoea, grunting, intercostal recession and hypoxia.<br><br>Meconium aspiration (B) is a term complication; polycythaemia (C) and congenital heart disease (D) are not specifically caused by preterm delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q193
  {q:'Surfactant deficiency in preterm infants leads to:',
  o:['Hyperbilirubinemia','Respiratory distress syndrome','Necrotizing enterocolitis','Neonatal sepsis'],a:1,
  e:`Surfactant deficiency directly causes RDS in preterm infants. Surfactant, produced by type II pneumocytes, reduces alveolar surface tension and prevents end-expiratory collapse.<br><br>Without it, alveoli collapse with each breath, producing the classic triad of tachypnoea, grunting and subcostal recession. Exogenous surfactant replacement therapy, administered directly into the trachea after birth, is one of the most effective treatments in neonatal medicine and has dramatically reduced RDS mortality.<br><br>Hyperbilirubinaemia (A) results from haemolysis or hepatic immaturity; necrotising enterocolitis (C) involves intestinal ischaemia; neonatal sepsis (D) is from bacterial infection : all are distinct from surfactant deficiency.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q194
  {q:'A major maternal risk factor for preterm labour is:',
  o:['Previous preterm birth','Maternal obesity','Postdated pregnancy','Multiparity'],a:0,
  e:`Previous spontaneous preterm birth is the single strongest maternal risk factor for preterm labour in a subsequent pregnancy, with a recurrence risk of approximately 15–30% in subsequent pregnancy.<br><br>Women who have had one previous spontaneous preterm birth have a recurrence risk of approximately 15–30% in a subsequent pregnancy, rising with each additional preterm birth, making previous preterm birth the cornerstone of risk stratification in preterm labour prevention programmes.<br><br>Maternal obesity (B) modestly increases risk; postdated pregnancy (C) is the opposite of preterm; multiparity (D) is not a major independent risk factor for preterm labour.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q195
  {q:'Which condition increases uterine stretch and predisposes to preterm labour?',
  o:['Placenta previa','Maternal anemia','Multiple pregnancy','Oligohydramnios'],a:2,
  e:`Multiple pregnancy causes marked uterine overdistension from carrying two or more fetuses with their respective placentas and amniotic fluid volumes, which stretches the myometrium and triggers mechanotransduction pathways that upregulate oxytocin receptors, prostaglandin production and gap junction formation.<br><br>Directly initiating preterm labour: approximately 60% of twin pregnancies deliver before 37 weeks, with this uterine stretch mechanism being a key driver alongside increased rates of placental abruption and PPROM. polyhydramnios produces a similar stretch mechanism and is also associated with preterm labour.<br><br>Placenta previa (A) causes haemorrhage rather than stretch-mediated contractions; maternal anaemia (B) does not cause uterine stretch; oligohydramnios (D) is associated with IUGR and decreased, not increased, amniotic volume.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q196
  {q:'Which prostaglandin plays a key role in initiation of labour including preterm labour?',
  o:['Prostaglandin F1','Prostaglandin I2','Prostaglandin A2','Prostaglandin E2'],a:3,
  e:`Prostaglandin E2 (PGE2) plays a central role in the initiation of both term and preterm labour, promoting cervical ripening and enhancing myometrial contractility.<br><br>PGE2 promotes cervical ripening by increasing collagenase activity and water content in the cervical stroma (cervical softening) and simultaneously enhances myometrial oxytocin receptor expression and contractility : making it both a cervical ripening agent and a uterotonic.<br><br>Prostaglandin F1 (A) and A2 (C) are not the primary labour-initiating prostaglandins; prostaglandin I2 (prostacyclin) (B) is primarily a vasodilator and platelet inhibitor, not a labour-initiating agent.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q197
  {q:'Which infection may trigger preterm labour through inflammatory cytokine release?',
  o:['Bacterial vaginosis','Viral hepatitis','Tuberculosis','Malaria'],a:0,
  e:`Bacterial vaginosis triggers preterm labour through an inflammatory cascade: overgrowth of anaerobic organisms produces phospholipases that cleave arachidonic acid from membrane phospholipids and proteases that degrade the cervical extracellular matrix.<br><br>Women with BV have a two- to three-fold increased risk of spontaneous preterm birth, making BV screening and treatment in high-risk women a component of preterm prevention strategies.<br><br>Viral hepatitis (B), tuberculosis (C) and malaria (D) can complicate pregnancy but do not specifically trigger preterm labour through the vaginal inflammatory cytokine pathway.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q198
  {q:'A woman presents at 30 weeks with uterine contractions but no cervical change. What is the diagnosis?',
  o:['Active labour','False preterm labour','True preterm labour','Inevitable abortion'],a:1,
  e:`False preterm labour (Braxton Hicks contractions) is diagnosed when a woman presents with regular uterine contractions but with no objective cervical change, no progressive dilatation or effacement, on repeated examination.<br><br>Fetal fibronectin testing and transvaginal cervical length measurement are useful adjuncts when clinical assessment of cervical change is uncertain : a negative fFN test has a high negative predictive value for delivery within 7–14 days.<br><br>Active labour (A) and true preterm labour (C) both require cervical change; inevitable abortion (D) applies to threatened miscarriage with open os before viability, not at 30 weeks.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q199
  {q:'Which fetal complication is associated with prematurity?',
  o:['Polycythemia','Macrosomia','Intraventricular hemorrhage','Shoulder dystocia'],a:2,
  e:`Intraventricular haemorrhage (IVH) is a major neurological complication of prematurity, particularly in infants born before 32 weeks, arising from the fragility of the germinal matrix capillaries in the immature brain.<br><br>These capillaries lack the pericyte investment and autoregulatory mechanisms of mature cerebral vessels, making them susceptible to rupture with fluctuations in cerebral blood flow, hypoxia or acidosis in the immediate postnatal period.<br><br>Polycythaemia (A) occurs in post-term infants; macrosomia (B) is associated with maternal diabetes; shoulder dystocia (D) is a mechanical complication of macrosomia : none are complications of prematurity.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q200
  {q:'Which neonatal complication is strongly associated with prematurity and intestinal ischaemia?',
  o:['Congenital diaphragmatic hernia','Necrotizing enterocolitis','Neonatal jaundice','Meconium aspiration'],a:1,
  e:`Necrotising enterocolitis (NEC) is a devastating intestinal emergency strongly associated with prematurity, caused by immature gut immunity, bacterial overgrowth and intestinal ischaemia.<br><br>Immature gut immunity, pathogenic bacterial overgrowth and intestinal ischaemia lead to bacterial translocation and a fulminant inflammatory response causing intestinal necrosis. NEC carries a mortality of 20–30% and is one of the most feared neonatal complications of extreme preterm birth; surgical resection of necrotic bowel is often required, risking short gut syndrome.<br><br>Congenital diaphragmatic hernia (A) is a developmental defect; neonatal jaundice (C) is common but not specifically intestinal; meconium aspiration (D) is a term complication.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q201
  {q:'The most important benefit of tocolysis in preterm labour is to:',
  o:['Increase fetal growth','Prevent infection','Allow time for corticosteroid administration','Prevent labour completely'],a:2,
  e:`The most important clinical benefit of tocolysis in preterm labour is to delay delivery sufficiently to allow a course of antenatal corticosteroids (betamethasone) to take effect.<br><br>Requiring a minimum of 24 hours but ideally 48 hours: tocolysis does not prevent preterm birth or significantly improve long-term neonatal outcomes when used alone, but the 48-hour window it creates for steroid administration substantially reduces the incidence and severity of respiratory distress syndrome.<br><br>Tocolytics do not increase fetal growth (A), prevent infection (B) or permanently prevent labour (D) : their value is entirely in buying time for the corticosteroid course.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q202
  {q:'Which drug class acts as a calcium channel blocker for tocolysis?',
  o:['Indomethacin','Ritodrine','Magnesium sulfate','Nifedipine'],a:3,
  e:`Nifedipine is the calcium channel blocker used as a tocolytic in preterm labour: it blocks voltage-gated L-type calcium channels in myometrial smooth muscle, reducing intracellular calcium availability and inhibiting the calcium-dependent phosphorylation of myosin light chains necessary for myometrial contraction.<br><br>Nifedipine has become the preferred tocolytic in many centres due to its oral availability, favourable side-effect profile compared with ritodrine and its superiority over magnesium sulphate and indomethacin in some comparative studies.<br><br>Indomethacin (A) is a COX inhibitor; ritodrine (B) is a beta-2 agonist; magnesium sulphate (C) is a calcium antagonist but acts primarily as a neuromuscular blocker rather than a direct calcium channel blocker.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q203
  {q:'Indomethacin suppresses uterine contractions by inhibiting:',
  o:['Prostaglandin synthesis','Oxytocin release','Progesterone metabolism','Estrogen production'],a:0,
  e:`Indomethacin suppresses uterine contractions by inhibiting cyclo-oxygenase (COX) enzymes, specifically COX-1 and COX-2, and thereby reducing the synthesis of prostaglandins PGE2 and PGF2-alpha that drive cervical ripening and myometrial contractions.<br><br>As a non-selective COX inhibitor, indomethacin is an effective tocolytic for 48–72 hours but its use is typically limited to before 32 weeks due to concerns about premature closure of the ductus arteriosus and fetal renal impairment with prolonged use.<br><br>Indomethacin does not affect oxytocin release (B), progesterone metabolism (C) or oestrogen production (D).<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q204
  {q:'A fetus born at 28 weeks is at highest risk of which neurological complication?',
  o:['Cerebral palsy','Hydrocephalus','Intraventricular hemorrhage','Epilepsy'],a:2,
  e:`IVH is the neurological complication of highest immediate risk in a 28-week infant, susceptible to haemorrhage from minor fluctuations in cerebral blood pressure.<br><br>The germinal matrix, a fragile vascular subependymal region that involutes only by 34–36 weeks, ruptures readily with minor fluctuations in cerebral blood pressure during the haemodynamic instability of the neonatal period. Grade III and IV IVH carry a high risk of post-haemorrhagic hydrocephalus, periventricular leukomalacia and long-term neurodevelopmental impairment including cerebral palsy.<br><br>Cerebral palsy (A) is a long-term outcome that may result from IVH; hydrocephalus (B) is a secondary complication of severe IVH; epilepsy (D) is a later consequence rather than the immediate neurological risk.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q205
  {q:'A common long-term complication of prematurity affecting vision is:',
  o:['Retinopathy of prematurity','Cataract','Optic neuritis','Glaucoma'],a:0,
  e:`Retinopathy of prematurity (ROP) is a proliferative retinal vascular disorder that occurs exclusively in premature infants, predominantly affecting infants born before 32 weeks or weighing under 1,500 g.<br><br>Particularly those born before 32 weeks or weighing less than 1,500 g: in utero, retinal vascularisation is driven by the relative retinal hypoxia of normal fetal development; after preterm birth, hyperoxia from supplemental oxygen disrupts this process, causing pathological neovascularisation that can progress to retinal detachment and blindness if untreated.<br><br>Cataract (B), optic neuritis (C) and glaucoma (D) are not specifically caused by prematurity or oxygen exposure in the neonatal period.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q206
  {q:'Which intervention is recommended in women with previous spontaneous preterm birth to reduce recurrence?',
  o:['Antibiotics','Progesterone therapy','Oxytocin infusion','Daily estrogen'],a:1,
  e:`Vaginal progesterone therapy, administered from approximately 16–24 weeks until 36 weeks, is recommended in women with previous spontaneous preterm birth and a short cervix (less than 25 mm) detected on transvaginal ultrasound.<br><br>Progesterone maintains uterine quiescence by blocking gap junction formation and oxytocin receptor upregulation, and its supplementation in high-risk women has demonstrated a significant reduction in recurrence of preterm birth in randomised trials.<br><br>Antibiotics (A) are used for specific infections, not prophylactically for preterm prevention; oxytocin infusion (C) stimulates labour; daily oestrogen (D) would promote labour onset rather than prevent it.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q207
  {q:'Cervical cerclage is indicated in:',
  o:['Polyhydramnios','Placenta previa','Cervical incompetence','Fetal macrosomia'],a:2,
  e:`Cervical cerclage is indicated for cervical incompetence, where the cervix dilates painlessly in the second trimester without contractions, causing recurrent mid-trimester losses or very preterm births.<br><br>It is also indicated in women with previous spontaneous preterm birth and a cervical length below 25 mm detected on transvaginal ultrasound surveillance in the current pregnancy.<br><br>Polyhydramnios (A) is managed by amnioreduction; placenta previa (B) is managed by caesarean section planning; macrosomia (D) is managed by glucose control and delivery planning.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q208
  {q:'Which hormone level increases toward term and contributes to labour onset?',
  o:['Estrogen','hCG','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:0,
  e:`Oestrogen levels rise progressively toward term and contribute to labour onset by increasing myometrial oxytocin receptor expression, upregulating connexin-43 gap junction formation between myometrial cells and stimulating prostaglandin synthesis.<br><br>All of which promote coordinated uterine contractions: the rising oestrogen-to-progesterone ratio in late pregnancy shifts the uterus from a quiescent state to a contractile state, contributing to the physiological transition into labour.<br><br>hCG (B) declines after the first trimester; prolactin (C) is primarily involved in lactation; progesterone (D) actively maintains quiescence and is the functional opponent of oestrogen in labour initiation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q209
  {q:'Which fetal hormone is believed to play a role in triggering labour?',
  o:['Insulin','Thyroxine','Growth hormone','Fetal cortisol'],a:3,
  e:`Fetal cortisol is the fetal hormone believed to play a key role in triggering the onset of labour, stimulating placental oestrogen production from androgen precursors.<br><br>Rising fetal cortisol in late gestation stimulates placental 17-hydroxylase activity, converting progesterone to androgen precursors that are then aromatised to oestrogens : thereby shifting the placental oestrogen-to-progesterone ratio and contributing to the functional progesterone withdrawal that initiates labour in human pregnancy.<br><br>Insulin (A) is involved in fetal growth and glucose homeostasis; thyroxine (B) regulates fetal metabolism; growth hormone (C) drives fetal growth : none are implicated in labour initiation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q210 : rotated: correct=B (prev Q209=D)
  {q:'The most reliable imaging technique to assess cervical length in preterm labour risk is:',
  o:['CT scan','Transvaginal ultrasound','Transabdominal ultrasound','MRI'],a:1,
  e:`Transvaginal ultrasound is the most reliable and accurate imaging technique for cervical length measurement in preterm labour risk assessment, without the limitations of bladder filling or maternal habitus.<br><br>A cervical length below 25 mm on transvaginal ultrasound in an asymptomatic high-risk woman or in the context of preterm labour symptoms is the key threshold triggering clinical intervention.<br><br>CT scan (A) involves ionising radiation and is not used for cervical assessment; transabdominal ultrasound (C) is less accurate; MRI (D) is not routinely used for cervical length measurement.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q211 : rotated: correct=A (prev Q210=B)
  {q:'Which type of diabetes is first recognized during pregnancy?',
  o:['Gestational diabetes mellitus','Type 1 diabetes mellitus','Maturity-onset diabetes of the young','Type 2 diabetes mellitus'],a:0,
  e:`Gestational diabetes mellitus (GDM) is defined as glucose intolerance that is first recognised during pregnancy, regardless of whether it existed prior to conception or resolves after delivery.<br><br>Women at high risk of GDM, including those with previous GDM, BMI above 30, family history and previous macrosomic infant, should be screened with a 75 g OGTT at 24–28 weeks.<br><br>Type 1 (B) and Type 2 (D) diabetes pre-exist pregnancy; MODY (C) is a monogenic form of diabetes that may first present during pregnancy but has a specific genetic diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q212
  {q:'The screening test commonly used for gestational diabetes at 24-28 weeks is:',
  o:['Fasting blood glucose','Oral glucose tolerance test','HbA1c measurement','Random blood glucose'],a:1,
  e:`The 75 g oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) at 24–28 weeks is the standard screening and diagnostic test for gestational diabetes.<br><br>Women at high risk of developing gestational diabetes should be offered an early OGTT and a repeat test at 24–28 weeks if the early test is normal.<br><br>Fasting blood glucose (A) alone is insufficient for diagnosis; HbA1c (C) reflects chronic glycaemia and is not reliable in pregnancy; random blood glucose (D) is non-specific.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q213
  {q:'Which fetal complication is most strongly associated with poorly controlled maternal diabetes?',
  o:['Intrauterine growth restriction','Oligohydramnios','Macrosomia','Microcephaly'],a:2,
  e:`Macrosomia, fetal birthweight above 4 kg or above the 90th percentile, is the most common and clinically important fetal complication of poorly controlled maternal diabetes.<br><br>Persistent maternal hyperglycaemia crosses the placenta, stimulating fetal pancreatic beta cells to produce excess insulin (fetal hyperinsulinaemia), which acts as a potent fetal growth factor driving deposition of fat and glycogen particularly in insulin-sensitive tissues including the liver, heart and subcutaneous fat.<br><br>IUGR (A) and oligohydramnios (B) are associated with pre-eclampsia; microcephaly (D) is associated with intrauterine infections and severe first-trimester folic acid deficiency.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q214 : rotated: correct=D (prev Q213=C)
  {q:'The most common congenital anomaly associated with pregestational diabetes is:',
  o:['Neural tube defect','Renal agenesis','Cleft palate','Ventricular septal defect'],a:3,
  e:`Ventricular septal defect (VSD) is the most common specific congenital cardiac anomaly associated with pregestational diabetes mellitus, caused by periconceptional hyperglycaemia disrupting cardiac septation.<br><br>Congenital heart disease overall occurs 2–5 times more frequently in infants of diabetic mothers compared to the general population, making preconception glucose optimisation the most important preventive strategy.<br><br>Neural tube defects (A) are associated with folic acid deficiency; renal agenesis (B) and cleft palate (C) are less common than cardiac anomalies in diabetic pregnancies.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q215 : rotated: correct=C (prev Q214=D)
  {q:'A newborn of a diabetic mother is most likely to develop which metabolic complication?',
  o:['Hyperglycemia','Hypernatremia','Hypoglycemia','Metabolic alkalosis'],a:2,
  e:`Neonatal hypoglycaemia is the most common metabolic complication in a newborn of a diabetic mother: during intrauterine life, fetal hyperinsulinaemia develops in response to chronic maternal hyperglycaemia crossing the placenta.<br><br>At birth, when the maternal glucose supply is abruptly cut, the newborn's excess insulin continues to act on a suddenly glucose-deprived circulation, causing rapid and potentially severe neonatal hypoglycaemia in the first hours of life.<br><br>Hyperglycaemia (A) is not the neonatal risk : the risk is hypoglycaemia from excess insulin; hypernatraemia (B) and metabolic alkalosis (D) are not expected complications of maternal diabetes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q216
  {q:'Which drug is considered the first-line pharmacological treatment for diabetes during pregnancy?',
  o:['Metformin','Glyburide','Pioglitazone','Insulin'],a:3,
  e:`Insulin is the first-line pharmacological treatment for diabetes in pregnancy : both gestational diabetes requiring pharmacological therapy and pre-existing diabetes.<br><br>Insulin therapy in pregnancy requires dose adjustment throughout gestation as insulin resistance progressively increases, and is typically divided into basal and bolus components to optimise glycaemic control.<br><br>Metformin (A) and glyburide (B) cross the placenta and are used in some centres but are not universally approved as first-line agents; pioglitazone (C) is contraindicated in pregnancy due to limited safety data.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q217
  {q:'The most common maternal complication associated with diabetes in pregnancy is:',
  o:['Pre-eclampsia','Postpartum hemorrhage','Placenta previa','Abruptio placentae'],a:0,
  e:`Pre-eclampsia is the most common serious maternal complication of diabetes in pregnancy: the shared pathophysiology of endothelial dysfunction and abnormal placentation in diabetic and pre-eclamptic pregnancies creates a significantly elevated risk.<br><br>Risk factors for pre-eclampsia associated with diabetes in pregnancy include pre-existing hypertension, nephropathy, poor glycaemic control and obesity : all common in women with long-standing Type 1 or Type 2 diabetes.<br><br>PPH (B), placenta previa (C) and placental abruption (D) are recognised but less common maternal complications of diabetic pregnancy than pre-eclampsia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q218
  {q:'Which fetal cardiac condition is associated with maternal diabetes?',
  o:['Tetralogy of Fallot','Transposition of great arteries','Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy','Coarctation of aorta'],a:2,
  e:`Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is the characteristic fetal cardiac complication of maternal diabetes, arising from the trophic effects of fetal hyperinsulinaemia on cardiac muscle growth.<br><br>Insulin acts as a potent growth factor in fetal cardiac tissue, producing pathological hypertrophy of the interventricular septum and ventricular walls that may cause dynamic left ventricular outflow tract obstruction in severe cases, typically resolving spontaneously within weeks to months after birth once hyperinsulinaemia resolves.<br><br>Tetralogy of Fallot (A), transposition of great arteries (B) and coarctation (D) are structural defects associated with periconceptional hyperglycaemia, not the functional hypertrophic pattern driven by fetal hyperinsulinaemia.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q219 : rotated: correct=C (prev Q218=C)
  {q:'Chronic hypertension in pregnancy is defined as hypertension diagnosed:',
  o:['Before pregnancy or before 20 weeks gestation','After 20 weeks gestation','Only during labour','After delivery'],a:0,
  e:`Chronic hypertension in pregnancy is defined as hypertension diagnosed before conception or before 20 completed weeks of gestation, virtually excluding gestational hypertension or pre-eclampsia as the cause.<br><br>Chronic hypertension in pregnancy carries risks of superimposed pre-eclampsia, fetal growth restriction and placental abruption, and requires careful monitoring and antihypertensive management with agents safe in pregnancy.<br><br>After 20 weeks (B) defines gestational hypertension; only during labour (C) is too narrow a definition; after delivery (D) describes postpartum hypertension.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q220 : rotated: correct=D (prev Q219=C)
  {q:'Gestational hypertension is defined as hypertension developing:',
  o:['Before 20 weeks gestation','Before pregnancy','With seizures during pregnancy','After 20 weeks gestation without proteinuria'],a:3,
  e:`Gestational hypertension is defined as new onset hypertension (blood pressure of 140/90 mmHg or above on two occasions at least 4 hours apart) developing after 20 weeks of gestation without proteinuria or other features of pre-eclampsia.<br><br>It is distinguished from chronic hypertension by its onset after 20 weeks, and from pre-eclampsia by the absence of significant proteinuria or end-organ involvement such as renal, hepatic or haematological dysfunction.<br><br>Before 20 weeks (A) and before pregnancy (B) define chronic hypertension; seizures with pre-eclampsia (C) defines eclampsia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q221 : rotated: correct=C (prev Q220=D)
  {q:'Which antihypertensive drug is commonly used as first-line treatment in pregnancy?',
  o:['Enalapril','Losartan','Labetalol','Atenolol'],a:2,
  e:`Labetalol, a combined alpha and beta blocker, is a commonly used first-line antihypertensive in pregnancy for both acute severe hypertension and chronic management.<br><br>It reduces peripheral resistance without significantly reducing uteroplacental blood flow, has a good safety profile in pregnancy with extensive clinical evidence, and is available in both oral and intravenous formulations for acute management of severe hypertension.<br><br>Enalapril (A) and losartan (B) are ACE inhibitors and angiotensin receptor blockers respectively : both are absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy due to fetal renal dysgenesis and oligohydramnios; atenolol (D) has been associated with fetal growth restriction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q222
  {q:'Which antihypertensive drug is contraindicated in pregnancy due to risk of fetal harm?',
  o:['Methyldopa','Hydralazine','Labetalol','Enalapril'],a:3,
  e:`Enalapril and all ACE inhibitors are absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy They block fetal angiotensin II, disrupting renal development with teratogenic consequences.<br><br>They block fetal angiotensin II, disrupting renal development and causing renal dysgenesis, severe oligohydramnios, pulmonary hypoplasia, limb contractures and neonatal renal failure. Collectively known as ACE inhibitor fetopathy. angiotensin receptor blockers (ARBs) carry identical risks and are equally contraindicated in pregnancy.<br><br>Methyldopa (A), hydralazine (B) and labetalol (C) are all safe antihypertensive options in pregnancy with established evidence bases and no fetopathic effects at recommended doses.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q223
  {q:'Severe hypertension in pregnancy is defined as blood pressure ≥:',
  o:['130/80 mmHg','140/90 mmHg','160/110 mmHg','150/95 mmHg'],a:2,
  e:`Severe hypertension in pregnancy is defined as a blood pressure of 160/110 mmHg or above: at this threshold the risk of maternal cerebrovascular accident (haemorrhagic stroke) is significantly increased, making immediate antihypertensive treatment mandatory.<br><br>Cerebral haemorrhage has been reported to be the most common cause of death in patients with eclampsia, underscoring the critical importance of controlling severe hypertension urgently.<br><br>130/80 mmHg (A) is a threshold for initiating antihypertensive treatment in some guidelines; 140/90 mmHg (B) defines standard hypertension; 150/95 mmHg (D) is moderately elevated but below the severe threshold.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q224
  {q:'Which fetal complication is most commonly associated with maternal hypertension?',
  o:['Macrosomia','Intrauterine growth restriction','Polyhydramnios','Fetal hydrops'],a:1,
  e:`Intrauterine growth restriction (IUGR) is the most common fetal complication of maternal hypertension in pregnancy: the mechanism is identical to the pre-eclampsia pathway.<br><br>IUGR associated with maternal hypertension typically presents as asymmetrical growth restriction with abnormal umbilical artery Doppler findings and requires close fetal surveillance and appropriately timed delivery.<br><br>Macrosomia (A) is associated with maternal diabetes; polyhydramnios (C) with diabetes and GI obstruction; fetal hydrops (D) with anaemia and cardiac failure : none are specifically caused by hypertension.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q225
  {q:'Which antihypertensive drug has historically been widely used and considered safe in pregnancy?',
  o:['Methyldopa','Captopril','Losartan','Propranolol'],a:0,
  e:`Methyldopa is the antihypertensive agent with the most extensive safety data in pregnancy : decades of clinical use and long-term follow-up studies of children exposed in utero showing no adverse neurodevelopmental outcomes.<br><br>Although labetalol and nifedipine have become preferred agents in many centres for their greater efficacy and simpler dosing, methyldopa is still widely used, particularly in the first trimester and in low-resource settings.<br><br>Captopril (B) and losartan (C) are ACE inhibitor and ARB respectively : both absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy; propranolol (D) has been associated with IUGR and neonatal bradycardia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q226
  {q:'Antiphospholipid antibody syndrome is characterized by:',
  o:['Increased platelet production','Hypercoagulable state','Severe anemia','Leukopenia'],a:1,
  e:`Antiphospholipid syndrome (APS) is characterised by a hypercoagulable state : persistent thrombophilia affecting both the arterial and venous circulations, and the uteroplacental vasculature.<br><br>Antiphospholipid antibodies (lupus anticoagulant, anti-cardiolipin antibodies, anti-beta-2 glycoprotein I antibodies) interfere with phospholipid-dependent coagulation reactions and activate endothelial cells and platelets, promoting thrombus formation in placental vessels, leading to pregnancy complications including recurrent miscarriage, placental thrombosis, pre-eclampsia and IUGR.<br><br>Increased platelet production (A) and leukopaenia (D) are not features of APS; severe anaemia (C) is not the primary haematological hallmark.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q227
  {q:'The most common pregnancy complication of antiphospholipid syndrome is:',
  o:['Recurrent miscarriage','Gestational diabetes','Polyhydramnios','Placenta previa'],a:0,
  e:`Recurrent miscarriage is the most common pregnancy complication of antiphospholipid syndrome (APS) and the most frequent reason women with APS are first investigated.<br><br>Antiphospholipid antibodies cause thrombosis in placental vessels, impairing trophoblast invasion and placental perfusion from early in the first trimester : producing early embryonic loss before 10 weeks, as well as second-trimester losses and late pregnancy complications including pre-eclampsia and placental abruption.<br><br>Gestational diabetes (B), polyhydramnios (C) and placenta previa (D) are not recognised pregnancy complications of APS.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q228 : rotated: correct=D (prev Q227=A)
  {q:'Which antibody is commonly detected in antiphospholipid syndrome?',
  o:['Anti-thyroid peroxidase','Anti-smooth muscle antibody','Anti-mitochondrial antibody','Anti-cardiolipin antibody'],a:3,
  e:`Anti-cardiolipin antibody (aCL) is the most commonly detected antibody in antiphospholipid syndrome and is included in the diagnostic criteria, along with lupus anticoagulant and anti-beta-2 glycoprotein I antibodies.<br><br>Along with lupus anticoagulant (the most specific test) and anti-beta-2 glycoprotein I antibodies, aCL forms part of the three antiphospholipid antibody criteria : positive results must be confirmed on two separate occasions at least 12 weeks apart to satisfy the Sapporo/revised Sapporo diagnostic criteria.<br><br>Anti-thyroid peroxidase (A) is found in Hashimoto thyroiditis; anti-smooth muscle (B) in autoimmune hepatitis; anti-mitochondrial (C) in primary biliary cholangitis : none are markers of APS.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q229 : rotated: correct=A (prev Q228=D)
  {q:'The lupus anticoagulant test is used to diagnose:',
  o:['Antiphospholipid syndrome','Systemic lupus erythematosus only','Hemophilia A','Von Willebrand disease'],a:0,
  e:`The lupus anticoagulant (LA) test, despite its name, is used to diagnose antiphospholipid syndrome, not SLE itself, not systemic lupus erythematosus, despite its misleading name.<br><br>Lupus anticoagulant is the most specific of the three antiphospholipid antibody tests, paradoxically prolonging in vitro clotting tests (APTT) while causing thrombosis in vivo by interfering with phospholipid-dependent coagulation steps; its detection confirms one of the three antibody criteria required for APS diagnosis.<br><br>SLE (B) is diagnosed using ANA, anti-dsDNA and clinical criteria : lupus anticoagulant may be present in SLE but does not diagnose SLE; haemophilia A (C) and von Willebrand disease (D) are factor deficiency disorders diagnosed by specific factor assays.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q230 : rotated: correct=D (prev Q229=A)
  {q:'A major obstetric complication associated with antiphospholipid syndrome is:',
  o:['Polyhydramnios','Post-term pregnancy','Fetal macrosomia','Placental thrombosis'],a:3,
  e:`Placental thrombosis is the key obstetric mechanism of antiphospholipid syndrome: antiphospholipid antibodies promote thrombosis in the intervillous space and spiral arteries, reducing placental perfusion and causing infarction.<br><br>This thrombotic placental pathology is the rationale for treating APS in pregnancy with aspirin plus low-molecular-weight heparin : the combination that reduces placental thrombosis and substantially improves live birth rates.<br><br>Polyhydramnios (A), post-term pregnancy (B) and macrosomia (C) are not recognised obstetric complications of APS.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q231 : rotated: correct=B (prev Q230=D)
  {q:'The standard treatment for pregnant women with antiphospholipid syndrome and recurrent miscarriage is:',
  o:['Corticosteroids alone','Aspirin plus heparin','Warfarin therapy','Methotrexate'],a:1,
  e:`Low-dose aspirin combined with low-molecular-weight heparin (LMWH) is the standard treatment for pregnant women with APS and recurrent miscarriage, demonstrated to improve live birth rates from approximately 40% to over 70%.<br><br>This combination has been demonstrated in randomised trials to significantly improve live birth rates in women with APS and recurrent miscarriage : from approximately 40% without treatment to over 70% with treatment.<br><br>Corticosteroids alone (A) are not effective for APS pregnancy complications; warfarin (C) is teratogenic in the first trimester; methotrexate (D) is an abortifacient.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q232 : rotated: correct=D (prev Q231=B)
  {q:'Warfarin is avoided during pregnancy primarily because it:',
  o:['Causes fetal anemia','Causes fetal growth restriction','Causes maternal hypertension','Causes teratogenic effects'],a:3,
  e:`Warfarin is avoided in pregnancy primarily because it is teratogenic It inhibits vitamin K-dependent fetal bone development and risks intracranial haemorrhage.<br><br>It crosses the placenta and inhibits vitamin K-dependent bone development between 6 and 12 weeks, producing warfarin embryopathy: nasal hypoplasia, stippled epiphyses and midface hypoplasia. In later pregnancy it risks fetal intracranial haemorrhage. LMWH is the preferred anticoagulant in pregnancy as it does not cross the placenta and carries no fetal teratogenic risk.<br><br>Fetal anaemia (A) and IUGR (B) are not the primary concerns with warfarin; maternal hypertension (C) is not caused by warfarin.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q233 : rotated: correct=C (prev Q232=D)
  {q:'Which autoimmune disease commonly affects women of reproductive age and may impact pregnancy?',
  o:['Rheumatoid arthritis','Multiple sclerosis','Systemic lupus erythematosus','Psoriasis'],a:2,
  e:`SLE predominantly affects women of reproductive age (female-to-male ratio 9:1) and has the broadest impact on pregnancy of any autoimmune disease.<br><br>It causes pre-eclampsia, fetal growth restriction, preterm birth, congenital heart block and neonatal lupus. Connective tissue diseases including SLE are specifically listed among conditions that increase risk of pre-eclampsia and IUGR, and women with SLE require close multidisciplinary antenatal surveillance.<br><br>Rheumatoid arthritis (A) often improves in pregnancy; multiple sclerosis (B) rarely causes obstetric complications; psoriasis (D) does not significantly affect pregnancy outcomes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q234 : rotated: correct=A (prev Q233=C)
  {q:'Women with systemic lupus erythematosus in pregnancy are at increased risk of:',
  o:['Pre-eclampsia','Macrosomia','Post-term pregnancy','Placenta previa'],a:0,
  e:`Women with SLE in pregnancy are at significantly increased risk of pre-eclampsia, 2–4 times the background risk, due to the shared pathophysiology of immune-mediated endothelial dysfunction, complement activation and abnormal placentation common to both conditions.<br><br>Distinguishing SLE flare from pre-eclampsia can be clinically challenging as both cause hypertension, renal dysfunction and proteinuria : complement levels (which fall in flare but rise in pre-eclampsia) may assist in differentiation.<br><br>Macrosomia (B) is associated with diabetes; post-term pregnancy (C) is not a recognised SLE complication; placenta previa (D) is not more common in SLE.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q235 : rotated: correct=C (prev Q234=A)
  {q:'Which antibody in SLE is associated with congenital heart block in the fetus?',
  o:['Anti-dsDNA','Anti-histone antibody','Anti-Ro (SSA) antibody','Anti-Sm antibody'],a:2,
  e:`Anti-Ro (SSA) antibody is the maternal SLE antibody specifically associated with congenital heart block in the fetus, capable of crossing the placenta and binding fetal atrioventricular node antigens.<br><br>Anti-Ro antibodies cross the placenta and bind to cardiac conduction tissue antigens in the developing fetal heart, causing inflammation and fibrosis of the atrioventricular node : resulting in varying degrees of heart block, most severely complete (third degree) AV block which carries significant perinatal mortality and requires permanent pacing in most affected infants.<br><br>Anti-dsDNA (A) causes lupus nephritis flare; anti-histone (B) is associated with drug-induced lupus; anti-Sm (D) is specific for SLE diagnosis but not for fetal complications.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q236
  {q:'Neonatal lupus is primarily associated with maternal antibodies against:',
  o:['SSA/Ro and SSB/La','dsDNA','Phospholipids','Histones'],a:0,
  e:`Neonatal lupus is caused by the transplacental passage of maternal SSA/Ro and SSB/La antibodies that bind to fetal cardiac and cutaneous antigens.<br><br>The syndrome includes transient neonatal rash (photosensitive erythematous rash), hepatitis, thrombocytopenia and, most seriously, congenital heart block, particularly complete AV block which may require permanent pacemaker implantation and carries a mortality of approximately 20%.<br><br>Anti-dsDNA (B) causes maternal nephritis flare; phospholipid antibodies (C) cause APS thrombosis; anti-histone antibodies (D) are associated with drug-induced lupus : none cause neonatal lupus.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q237
  {q:'Which complication may occur in pregnancies affected by antiphospholipid syndrome?',
  o:['Fetal macrosomia','Hydramnios','Intrauterine growth restriction','Shoulder dystocia'],a:2,
  e:`Intrauterine growth restriction (IUGR) is a recognised complication of antiphospholipid syndrome in pregnancy, arising from placental thrombosis and infarction that reduces functional placental mass and uteroplacental blood flow.<br><br>The same mechanism of placental vascular thrombosis that causes recurrent miscarriage in early pregnancy produces placental insufficiency and growth restriction in ongoing pregnancies : typically manifesting as asymmetrical IUGR with abnormal umbilical artery Doppler studies in the second and third trimesters.<br><br>Macrosomia (A), polyhydramnios (B) and shoulder dystocia (D) are complications of diabetes rather than APS.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q238 : rotated: correct=C (prev Q237=C)
  {q:'Which autoimmune condition is most strongly associated with recurrent second-trimester pregnancy loss?',
  o:['Rheumatoid arthritis','Antiphospholipid syndrome','Graves disease','Hashimoto thyroiditis'],a:1,
  e:`Antiphospholipid syndrome is the autoimmune condition most strongly associated with recurrent pregnancy loss, particularly second-trimester losses (after 10 weeks), which are more specific for APS than first-trimester losses.<br><br>Placental thrombosis and infarction impair placental function progressively during the second trimester, causing fetal demise at gestations where other causes of miscarriage (such as chromosomal abnormality) are less common, making APS the dominant cause of recurrent loss in this gestational window.<br><br>Rheumatoid arthritis (A), Graves disease (C) and Hashimoto thyroiditis (D) are not specifically associated with recurrent second-trimester loss.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q239 : rotated: correct=A (prev Q238=C)
  {q:'Low-dose aspirin in pregnancy primarily works by:',
  o:['Reducing platelet aggregation','Increasing prostaglandin synthesis','Increasing fibrin formation','Increasing coagulation factor production'],a:0,
  e:`Low-dose aspirin (75–150 mg daily) in pregnancy works primarily by irreversibly inhibiting platelet cyclo-oxygenase, preventing thromboxane A2 synthesis and thereby reducing platelet aggregation.<br><br>In APS, this anti-platelet effect reduces thrombotic tendency in placental vessels; in pre-eclampsia prevention, aspirin additionally inhibits COX-2-mediated prostacyclin synthesis in endothelial cells at higher doses but predominantly targets platelet thromboxane at low doses.<br><br>Increasing prostaglandin synthesis (B) would worsen platelet aggregation; aspirin does not increase fibrin formation (C) or coagulation factor production (D) : its action is anti-platelet and anti-inflammatory.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q240 : rotated: correct=B (prev Q239=A)
  {q:'In women with antiphospholipid syndrome, which anticoagulant is preferred during pregnancy?',
  o:['Warfarin','Low molecular weight heparin','Rivaroxaban','Dabigatran'],a:1,
  e:`LMWH is the preferred anticoagulant in pregnancy for women with antiphospholipid syndrome, without crossing the placenta or carrying teratogenic risk.<br><br>It does not cross the placenta, carries no teratogenic or fetal haemorrhagic risk, and effectively prevents both maternal thrombosis and placental vessel thrombosis. Making it the safest available anticoagulant for use throughout all trimesters. lMWH combined with low-dose aspirin is the standard dual therapy for APS in pregnancy, demonstrated to significantly improve live birth rates and reduce obstetric complications.<br><br>Warfarin (A) crosses the placenta and is teratogenic; rivaroxaban (C) and dabigatran (D) are direct oral anticoagulants with insufficient pregnancy safety data and potential fetal risks.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q241 : rotated: correct=D (prev Q240=B)
  {q:'Which screening test is recommended early in pregnancy for women with high risk of gestational diabetes?',
  o:['Oral glucose tolerance test','HbA1c','Random blood glucose','Fasting plasma glucose'],a:3,
  e:`Fasting plasma glucose is the recommended early screening test in high-risk women (previous GDM, BMI above 30, family history, previous macrosomic infant, certain ethnicities).<br><br>An early fasting glucose identifies women with pre-existing undiagnosed Type 2 diabetes or early gestational diabetes, as women at high risk for developing gestational diabetes should be offered an early OGTT : often preceded by an early fasting glucose to identify those who may already meet diagnostic thresholds without the need for the full OGTT.<br><br>Full OGTT (A) is used at 24–28 weeks; HbA1c (B) is unreliable in pregnancy; random blood glucose (C) is non-specific for diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q242
  {q:'The most common cause of fetal macrosomia in pregnancies complicated by diabetes is:',
  o:['Maternal hyperinsulinemia','Fetal hyperinsulinemia','Increased placental estrogen','Maternal hypoglycemia'],a:1,
  e:`Fetal hyperinsulinaemia is the direct cause of macrosomia in diabetic pregnancies: maternal hyperglycaemia crosses the placenta freely and chronically stimulates fetal pancreatic beta cells to produce excess insulin.<br><br>Fetal insulin then acts as a potent anabolic growth factor, driving excessive deposition of fat (particularly in the liver, heart and subcutaneous tissue), glycogen and protein, resulting in a large-for-gestational-age fetus with disproportionate truncal obesity.<br><br>Maternal hyperinsulinaemia (A) does not cross the placenta; increased placental oestrogen (C) is not the mechanism; maternal hypoglycaemia (D) would reduce, not increase, fetal growth.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
// Q243
  {q:'Which maternal metabolic disturbance in diabetes contributes to congenital malformations?',
  o:['Hypoglycemia','Hyperlipidemia','Hyperglycemia','Hypocalcemia'],a:2,
  e:`Maternal hyperglycaemia during the periconceptional period and the first 8 weeks of embryogenesis is the primary teratogenic mechanism responsible for congenital malformations in infants of diabetic mothers.<br><br>Excess glucose generates reactive oxygen species and disrupts yolk sac nutrient transport and arachidonic acid metabolism, interfering with normal organogenesis particularly of the heart, neural tube and skeleton : the organs undergoing critical morphogenesis during this window.<br><br>Hypoglycaemia (A) is a neonatal, not teratogenic, complication; hyperlipidaemia (B) and hypocalcaemia (D) are not the primary teratogenic mechanisms in diabetic pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q244
  {q:'Which complication of diabetes in pregnancy is associated with excessive amniotic fluid?',
  o:['Oligohydramnios','Polyhydramnios','Placental insufficiency','Placental abruption'],a:1,
  e:`Polyhydramnios, excessive amniotic fluid, is a recognised complication of diabetic pregnancy, arising from fetal hyperglycaemia-driven osmotic diuresis, producing excess fetal urine output that accumulates as polyhydramnios.<br><br>Fetal hyperglycaemia increases fetal urinary output as the kidneys excrete the excess glucose load, and fetal macrosomia from hyperinsulinaemia further amplifies amniotic fluid production; the result is polyhydramnios that can cause uterine overdistension, preterm labour, fetal malpresentation and umbilical cord prolapse.<br><br>Oligohydramnios (A) is associated with fetal renal anomalies and IUGR; placental insufficiency (C) and abruption (D) are complications of hypertension and smoking rather than diabetes-specific findings.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q245
  {q:'The most common cause of maternal mortality in women with systemic lupus erythematosus during pregnancy is:',
  o:['Severe anemia','Renal failure','Infection','Thromboembolism'],a:3,
  e:`Thromboembolism is the most common cause of maternal mortality in women with SLE during pregnancy, a leading cause of maternal death even in the era of anticoagulation.<br><br>The hypercoagulable state of SLE, amplified by pregnancy physiology and concurrent antiphospholipid antibodies, creates substantially elevated DVT and PE risk, a leading cause of maternal death even with modern anticoagulation. Women with SLE and antiphospholipid antibodies are at particularly high risk and require prophylactic or therapeutic LMWH throughout pregnancy.<br><br>Severe anaemia (A), renal failure (B) and infection (C) are important complications of SLE in pregnancy but are individually less common causes of maternal death than thromboembolism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q246
  {q:'Which laboratory test is most specific for diagnosing antiphospholipid syndrome?',
  o:['Antinuclear antibody','Anti-dsDNA antibody','Lupus anticoagulant test','Rheumatoid factor'],a:2,
  e:`The lupus anticoagulant (LA) test is the most specific laboratory test for diagnosing antiphospholipid syndrome among the three antiphospholipid antibody criteria.<br><br>A positive LA that persists on repeat testing after 12 weeks satisfies one of the three laboratory criteria required for formal APS diagnosis under the revised Sapporo criteria.<br><br>ANA (A) screens for autoimmune disease generally; anti-dsDNA (B) is specific for SLE nephritis; rheumatoid factor (D) is for rheumatoid arthritis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q247
  {q:'Which hypertensive disorder of pregnancy is characterized by hypertension, proteinuria and multi-organ dysfunction?',
  o:['Chronic hypertension','Pre-eclampsia','Gestational hypertension','White coat hypertension'],a:1,
  e:`Pre-eclampsia is defined by hypertension developing after 20 weeks combined with significant proteinuria and/or evidence of multi-organ dysfunction, driven by abnormal placentation and anti-angiogenic placental factors.<br><br>Including renal, hepatic, haematological, neurological or placental involvement: it is a potentially life-threatening hypertensive disorder characterised by vascular dysfunction and systemic inflammation involving the brain, liver and kidneys of the mother, driven by abnormal placentation and anti-angiogenic placental factors.<br><br>Chronic hypertension (A) predates pregnancy; gestational hypertension (C) lacks proteinuria and organ involvement; white coat hypertension (D) is clinic-only elevation without true hypertension.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q248
  {q:'Which antihypertensive drug is commonly used intravenously for acute severe hypertension in pregnancy?',
  o:['Hydralazine','Methyldopa','Enalapril','Losartan'],a:0,
  e:`Hydralazine, administered intravenously, is a widely used treatment for acute severe hypertension in pregnancy and the hypertensive emergency of pre-eclampsia.<br><br>Intravenous labetalol is an equally effective alternative and has become preferred in many centres; sublingual nifedipine is also used in acute severe hypertension when IV access is not immediately available.<br><br>Methyldopa (B) is for chronic management, not acute hypertensive emergency; enalapril (C) and losartan (D) are absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q249 : rotated: correct=B (prev Q248=A)
  {q:'Which fetal complication may occur in infants of diabetic mothers due to delayed lung maturity?',
  o:['Meconium aspiration','Respiratory distress syndrome','Pulmonary hypoplasia','Congenital diaphragmatic hernia'],a:1,
  e:`Respiratory distress syndrome (RDS) occurs more frequently in infants of diabetic mothers than in gestation-matched controls because hyperinsulinaemia delays fetal lung maturation.<br><br>Specifically inhibiting surfactant phospholipid synthesis by type II pneumocytes: insulin interferes with cortisol-stimulated surfactant production, meaning that even at 37–38 weeks an infant of a poorly controlled diabetic mother may have the surfactant profile of a significantly less mature infant, increasing RDS risk with elective delivery before 39 weeks.<br><br>Meconium aspiration (A) and congenital diaphragmatic hernia (C) are not specifically caused by maternal diabetes; pulmonary hypoplasia (D) is associated with oligohydramnios from renal agenesis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
// Q250 : rotated: correct=C (prev Q249=B)
  {q:'Which obstetric complication is increased in women with chronic hypertension during pregnancy?',
  o:['Placenta accreta','Uterine rupture','Placental abruption','Shoulder dystocia'],a:2,
  e:`Placental abruption is significantly increased in women with chronic hypertension during pregnancy: the underlying arterial disease and impaired decidual vascularisation associated with chronic hypertension predispose to spiral artery pathology and reduced uteroplacental perfusion.<br><br>The same vascular compromise that causes the decidual necrosis and retroplacental haematoma formation underlying placental abruption; risk factors for placental abruption specifically include hypertension including pre-eclampsia, smoking, trauma, cocaine and polyhydramnios.<br><br>Placenta accreta (A) is related to previous uterine surgery; uterine rupture (B) to previous caesarean scar; shoulder dystocia (D) to macrosomia and diabetes : none are specifically related to chronic hypertension.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`}
  ];
})();
